WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:17.900 --> 00:00:22.860
﻿﻿We have three clay courts.
Three here and three more there.

00:00:23.260 --> 00:00:25.500
A total of nine clay courts.

00:00:25.780 --> 00:00:30.260
We use the part intended
for basketball players to warm up.

00:00:30.500 --> 00:00:36.780
And that part over there
is the athletics tartan track.

00:00:37.540 --> 00:00:41.820
There is also a completely new
concrete part with a hall behind it.

00:00:42.060 --> 00:00:50.060
When we came here none of that existed.
There were only these clay courts.

00:00:50.303 --> 00:00:53.701
And everything else is built.
And only for six months.

00:00:55.620 --> 00:00:58.620
Everything happens
pretty fast with you?

00:00:59.140 --> 00:01:03.780
Having good partners
is the key to my success.

00:01:04.140 --> 00:01:08.620
Would you like to come downstairs
so I can show you the tartan track.

00:01:09.220 --> 00:01:15.060
It's really great.
I think it's about 36 meters long.

00:01:15.300 --> 00:01:19.460
So everyone can use it.
-This micro location is ideal.

00:01:21.740 --> 00:01:23.580
A wonderful place to sweat.

00:01:23.860 --> 00:01:27.540
Athletes who come here
have a hotel where they can eat,

00:01:27.780 --> 00:01:30.780
get ready and come to training.

00:01:31.020 --> 00:01:36.820
They have a sea where they can swim,
from March until November.

00:01:38.900 --> 00:01:42.220
It's nice. -What more
could you want than that.

00:01:42.549 --> 00:01:46.499
Who do you think used the court first?
-Pete Sampras. -You won't guess.

00:01:47.775 --> 00:01:53.695
The first two people who played on this
court are Roger Federer's children.

00:01:54.020 --> 00:01:57.260
He came here in the summer when
the fields were supposed to be finished.

00:01:57.620 --> 00:02:01.380
The first two people to enter
the field were his two sons.

00:02:01.620 --> 00:02:04.020
They played here on the courts.

00:02:04.260 --> 00:02:10.140
We have one concrete court here, and there
are two more concrete courts up there.

00:02:10.380 --> 00:02:13.540
There are balloons on them,
so we can still play.

00:02:13.820 --> 00:02:17.220
And behind them is a hall
that is phenomenal.

00:02:17.500 --> 00:02:20.660
We have heating in it and
all other conditions. -Congratulations.

00:02:26.300 --> 00:02:31.020
Ljubo, good afternoon.
I really thank you for your time.

00:02:32.620 --> 00:02:38.180
Long time no see, twenty years
have passed since our last meeting.

00:02:38.460 --> 00:02:42.340
It was on the Olympic Games
in Athens in 2004.

00:02:42.540 --> 00:02:45.329
It was a lineup. -That's right.

00:02:46.836 --> 00:02:52.993
I thank you for being a guest on the show
and for talking about your life.

00:02:54.100 --> 00:02:59.820
I'm glad to see you again. -Thank you.
Thanks for the invitation.

00:03:00.300 --> 00:03:04.940
I'm always happy to expand
the view of my life to people

00:03:05.220 --> 00:03:08.380
who don't know it,
and there are many of them.

00:03:09.060 --> 00:03:14.860
Yes, 20 years have passed since Athens
and beautiful sports moments.

00:03:15.740 --> 00:03:22.738
We were in the army together.
-We even have evidence for that.

00:03:24.540 --> 00:03:30.780
Thanks for the invitation.
I'm glad to see you. After all this time.

00:03:31.860 --> 00:03:37.027
Ljubo, before the very beginning
and the conversation about your life.

00:03:37.820 --> 00:03:41.540
In the beginning,
you will be our tour guide.

00:03:41.820 --> 00:03:47.820
We are located on the island of Lošinj,
where you organized the academy.

00:03:48.100 --> 00:03:51.900
All this we see around us
is really impressive.

00:03:52.180 --> 00:03:54.540
There are many children
who speak different languages.

00:03:54.820 --> 00:03:59.420
Can you tell us a little more about
this project of yours and your goals.

00:03:59.860 --> 00:04:03.980
A lot has happened in your life.
Tell us more about all that.

00:04:04.860 --> 00:04:09.740
What we have built here and what
we will deal with is a summary

00:04:10.020 --> 00:04:13.420
of everything I know and what
I have experienced playing tennis.

00:04:14.020 --> 00:04:22.580
From 1992-1993 when I was in Italy
in the club for three or four years.

00:04:22.860 --> 00:04:28.300
Which looked something like this.

00:04:28.780 --> 00:04:34.020
A place where promising players who want
to become professionals one day gather.

00:04:34.740 --> 00:04:41.855
My experience as a player, trainer
and TV commentator, I try everything...

00:04:44.800 --> 00:04:51.448
Pass on to the young. -That's right.
This gym we are in now is specific.

00:04:51.909 --> 00:04:58.589
There are no weights in it.
We follow modern training methods.

00:04:59.162 --> 00:05:05.423
This place is like a fairy tale.
Absolute paradise.

00:05:06.260 --> 00:05:10.980
We have best conditions in the world.
Everything we need is here.

00:05:11.260 --> 00:05:16.180
We are isolated from the public,
and that is ideal for training,

00:05:16.255 --> 00:05:18.335
for focus and concentration.

00:05:19.420 --> 00:05:21.540
I'm happy about that.

00:05:21.860 --> 00:05:26.900
We did something, and that is that
people come back here again.

00:05:27.220 --> 00:05:31.620
We get more and more calls.
But we have limited capacity.

00:05:31.900 --> 00:05:35.765
And it happened that we even
started rejecting players,

00:05:35.915 --> 00:05:38.075
and that was not our goal.

00:05:38.660 --> 00:05:44.220
In terms of infrastructure you are
covered with courts... What's in here?

00:05:44.540 --> 00:05:48.251
As for the tennis courts,
we have nine clay courts.

00:05:48.396 --> 00:05:53.369
Here in Veli Lošinj, outdoors.
We have four concrete courts.

00:05:53.561 --> 00:05:58.290
One of them is with a fixed structure,
it is a closed type.

00:05:58.391 --> 00:06:00.744
And on the other three courts,
we have the option to put on

00:06:00.844 --> 00:06:02.822
and take off balloons,
depending on the need.

00:06:02.936 --> 00:06:05.416
That's what Veli Lošinj is all about.

00:06:06.133 --> 00:06:12.790
We also have them in Mali Lošinj,
which we use the most during tournaments.

00:06:14.220 --> 00:06:20.104
In June, the European Senior Championship
of all categories is played here.

00:06:20.281 --> 00:06:23.601
When 350 players come from
all over the world because it is

00:06:23.802 --> 00:06:25.482
an open championship.

00:06:25.636 --> 00:06:30.320
Then we use all the courts on the island.
Our infrastructure is truly top-notch.

00:06:30.580 --> 00:06:33.940
We lack absolutely nothing.
We have everything.

00:06:34.180 --> 00:06:38.660
We have sponsors who send us balls,
rackets and everything we need.

00:06:41.420 --> 00:06:43.420
So everything is great.

00:06:43.660 --> 00:06:48.887
I'm not saying that because it's mine.
But I am quite demanding.

00:06:50.540 --> 00:06:56.980
When I see how much youth,
dreams, thinking, illusions are here,

00:06:57.380 --> 00:07:03.172
can you imagine and draw a parallel
with some of your beginnings

00:07:03.695 --> 00:07:08.260
at the age of 10 or 11 in Banja Luka.

00:07:09.060 --> 00:07:13.180
Compare today's conditions
with how you grew up.

00:07:13.460 --> 00:07:17.060
How young people
thing today.

00:07:17.900 --> 00:07:22.540
I'm going to sound a little silly now,
but the first thing that comes to mind

00:07:22.860 --> 00:07:28.140
are cell phones, iPads, technology
that has changed the way of life.

00:07:28.860 --> 00:07:33.420
It is the present, it is modern.
You can't do without it today.

00:07:33.700 --> 00:07:38.580
There was a period some ten years ago
when we might have been able

00:07:38.860 --> 00:07:41.420
to do something about it.
But, it's too late.

00:07:41.700 --> 00:07:45.340
As parents, as a coach, we cannot
tell children not to use cell phones.

00:07:45.540 --> 00:07:49.460
We know it's harmful,
we don't know how much.

00:07:50.180 --> 00:07:55.620
When we talk about beginning and
what I remember. I remember training.

00:07:55.860 --> 00:08:00.460
I ran in the forest, played
basketball, football, handball.

00:08:00.740 --> 00:08:08.020
Everything that childhood offered.
Today it is totally different.

00:08:08.368 --> 00:08:11.462
Today, we very quickly starts
to engage in professional sports

00:08:11.602 --> 00:08:14.002
or at least the idea of ​​professionalism.

00:08:15.220 --> 00:08:19.820
For children today sport does not
represent what it represented to us.

00:08:20.140 --> 00:08:23.660
Everything is highlights,
everything is short, everything is quick.

00:08:23.940 --> 00:08:27.300
There is an overwhelming amount
of information that confuses children

00:08:27.500 --> 00:08:29.700
more than it helps them.

00:08:30.020 --> 00:08:36.500
These are today's challenges for trainers
and for the people who try to teach

00:08:36.780 --> 00:08:45.460
them life, sports, tennis and everything
that is needed for top sport.

00:08:45.740 --> 00:08:50.380
And that is the idea of ​​every
child who comes to Lošinj.

00:08:50.740 --> 00:08:56.300
Last year the Italian TV company Sky
made a documentary about your life

00:08:56.477 --> 00:09:01.718
and for the first time since 1992
you went to your birthplace.

00:09:01.847 --> 00:09:04.607
In Lužani near Banja Luka.

00:09:05.540 --> 00:09:10.540
For the first time after many years,
the emotions are certainly there.

00:09:10.740 --> 00:09:13.100
Can it be described with words?

00:09:13.300 --> 00:09:16.820
How did you feel and did you meet
someone from your childhood?

00:09:17.020 --> 00:09:25.420
Or is it a story you've long forgotten?
-Yes, I am quite far from all that.

00:09:25.660 --> 00:09:33.380
It was emotional. I don't think I can
describe it, because it's hard for me.

00:09:36.300 --> 00:09:41.140
In the very beginning, there was
no possibility to return home.

00:09:41.420 --> 00:09:45.900
Then there was a period when you
didn't want it and then there was

00:09:46.100 --> 00:09:49.140
a period when you
no longer have time.

00:09:49.340 --> 00:09:54.940
And so 30 years pass. -That is the reason
why I was not in Banja Luka.

00:09:56.860 --> 00:10:01.180
Now we decided to make that
documentary which is beautiful

00:10:01.287 --> 00:10:03.367
and I am really very satisfied.

00:10:03.505 --> 00:10:05.860
It was recorded in two parts,
twice for 40 minutes.

00:10:06.036 --> 00:10:08.899
The first part talks about childhood
and beginnings, and the second part

00:10:09.021 --> 00:10:11.541
talks about tennis from 1999
until the end of his career.

00:10:11.844 --> 00:10:16.337
Excuse me, will we be able to watch
that here? With subtitles.

00:10:16.460 --> 00:10:18.620
If anyone is interested.

00:10:20.660 --> 00:10:24.460
I am not the owner of the rights,
but if anyone is interested,

00:10:24.700 --> 00:10:27.700
please contact Sky Television.

00:10:27.980 --> 00:10:34.660
I want to say it was emotional, but not
in the way that I was angry, sad, happy.

00:10:34.860 --> 00:10:37.580
But just a strong emotion.

00:10:37.820 --> 00:10:43.500
It's like I unblocked some part
that I didn't know was blocked.

00:10:43.900 --> 00:10:46.260
I cried all day.

00:10:47.100 --> 00:10:55.900
There were tears and emotions, as if
my whole life had passed before my eyes.

00:10:56.580 --> 00:11:02.300
Suddenly, and I rarely do that,
I started thinking about my life journey,

00:11:02.460 --> 00:11:06.580
not only about Banja Luka,
but about my whole life journey.

00:11:06.780 --> 00:11:10.075
I'm just not that kind of guy,
I only think about today

00:11:10.225 --> 00:11:13.442
and maybe a little ahead,
never about the past.

00:11:13.644 --> 00:11:17.007
In the beginning it was some kind
of defense system

00:11:17.630 --> 00:11:20.788
so that you don't think about it.

00:11:21.080 --> 00:11:26.040
I dreamed about my childhood
for a very long time, but not anymore.

00:11:26.639 --> 00:11:31.313
Until five or ten years ago,
I dreamed about my school friends

00:11:31.500 --> 00:11:33.992
from Banja Luka and
about my life there.

00:11:34.420 --> 00:11:40.620
It is something that is drawn
and engraved in the memory.

00:11:42.380 --> 00:11:47.077
Even today I am in contact
with some of them.

00:11:47.660 --> 00:11:51.580
And now during this trip
I met my first coach.

00:11:51.820 --> 00:11:56.580
Not much has changed there.
It was beautiful.

00:11:58.300 --> 00:12:02.900
I didn't even know I needed that.
I'm glad that happened.

00:12:03.060 --> 00:12:07.380
Not because of the
negative connotations.

00:12:07.620 --> 00:12:20.340
Thirty something years have passed
and I was just glad to see some people.

00:12:20.660 --> 00:12:23.340
I came to the place
where it all actually began.

00:12:23.540 --> 00:12:27.900
What I didn't know was
that the club I played in, Mladost,

00:12:28.300 --> 00:12:31.740
was founded one year before
I started playing tennis.

00:12:31.980 --> 00:12:35.420
I thought that club existed
for a long time, that it had a tradition.

00:12:35.660 --> 00:12:40.860
And actually it was a new club.
A really beautiful club in the park.

00:12:41.100 --> 00:12:47.020
Where the ATP tournament
was held last year. It was nice for me.

00:12:47.220 --> 00:12:53.300
Emotional, but beautiful. -Was it
emotionally draining or drawing a line?

00:12:53.500 --> 00:12:56.500
Or both? -It was more a discharge.

00:12:56.700 --> 00:13:03.706
I don't like to draw lines.
I didn't say I'd never come back.

00:13:04.060 --> 00:13:05.740
Better to say discharge.

00:13:06.820 --> 00:13:10.820
I haven't used that word
in a long time,

00:13:11.060 --> 00:13:15.260
so I'll steal it from you
next time I'm asked.

00:13:20.540 --> 00:13:22.540
Let's go back to the beginning.

00:13:22.820 --> 00:13:28.900
Did you play any other sports
like football, basketball?

00:13:29.500 --> 00:13:32.626
Or was it just tennis
from the beginning?

00:13:33.260 --> 00:13:37.380
I started playing tennis relatively late
when I was 8 and a half or 9 years old.

00:13:37.512 --> 00:13:39.632
Which is quite late for tennis.

00:13:39.770 --> 00:13:42.570
Today, it is suggested that children
start practicing at the age of three,

00:13:42.717 --> 00:13:45.302
four, five or six at the most,
and that is because of coordination.

00:13:45.472 --> 00:13:48.381
Not because of physical fitness,
but because of the coordination

00:13:48.700 --> 00:13:51.660
to hold something in the hand
and to hit the ball.

00:13:52.060 --> 00:13:55.540
They explained to me
that it develops at that age.

00:13:55.900 --> 00:14:00.971
But considering that I grew up
with a ball that I threw, kicked,

00:14:01.139 --> 00:14:03.666
passed, that period passed quickly.

00:14:04.306 --> 00:14:11.026
It was not difficult for me
to hit the ball with the racket.

00:14:11.620 --> 00:14:15.260
I remember that before
I even started training tennis,

00:14:15.820 --> 00:14:21.140
I had plastic rackets and
a sponge ball that I used to hit.

00:14:21.380 --> 00:14:26.340
I was an active child
who did all kinds of sports.

00:14:26.580 --> 00:14:29.782
When I came home from school,
I would leave my bag in the room

00:14:29.949 --> 00:14:32.361
and go outside to play.
And I would come in the evening.

00:14:32.574 --> 00:14:35.183
That's what our
childhood looked like.

00:14:35.502 --> 00:14:38.540
I started playing tennis
by watching Wimbledon on TV.

00:14:38.726 --> 00:14:43.063
When my father asked me which sport
I would like to do more seriously.

00:14:43.199 --> 00:14:46.259
While I was watching Wimbledon
I told him it was tennis.

00:14:46.428 --> 00:14:49.829
Father didn't even know
if there was a club...

00:14:50.740 --> 00:14:53.820
He had no contact with tennis?
-Nothing at all.

00:14:54.180 --> 00:14:58.300
He asked his friends.
There used to be two tennis clubs.

00:14:58.464 --> 00:15:03.211
I don't know if they still exist.
Petar Drapšin and Mladen Stojanović.

00:15:04.860 --> 00:15:09.220
I decided on Mladost, I don't
know why, but that's how it started.

00:15:10.260 --> 00:15:16.100
During that younger period
until 1992 by the time he left,

00:15:16.380 --> 00:15:20.260
you had notable results
in Bosnia and Herzegovina.

00:15:20.500 --> 00:15:22.780
Is that true?
-Somewhere near the end.

00:15:23.060 --> 00:15:24.940
Not at the beginning,
because if I started playing

00:15:25.180 --> 00:15:28.420
in 1988 or 1989,
it wasn't until 1991.

00:15:28.620 --> 00:15:33.780
At the age of 12 I was among
the best in Bosnia.

00:15:34.660 --> 00:15:38.540
I went to Belgrade to participate
in the first international tournament.

00:15:38.820 --> 00:15:43.885
Where I beat some players
who on paper were better than me.

00:15:44.478 --> 00:15:48.737
Those were the first signs
that I had talent,

00:15:49.140 --> 00:15:52.780
because I only started playing
three or four years ago.

00:15:53.140 --> 00:15:57.100
Did you already have any contacts
with clubs then? -No.

00:15:58.220 --> 00:16:00.980
If there was no war, I would still be
living in Banja Luka

00:16:01.220 --> 00:16:03.180
and who knows what I would do.

00:16:03.420 --> 00:16:06.820
There was no such thing.

00:16:08.340 --> 00:16:11.260
All this that happened later,
I guess we will talk

00:16:11.500 --> 00:16:15.016
about that period as well,
it simply followed each other.

00:16:15.171 --> 00:16:18.805
In the beginning, there were
no big plans or ideas.

00:16:19.051 --> 00:16:22.511
I simply started doing sports,
I loved it and I was successful.

00:16:23.900 --> 00:16:27.180
Now we will move on to more
difficult topics,

00:16:27.540 --> 00:16:29.700
because the show is called
Champion's Failure

00:16:30.060 --> 00:16:32.060
so we're looking for some…

00:16:32.300 --> 00:16:35.060
There are many more failures.
-We come to the sad part.

00:16:35.300 --> 00:16:40.580
During that war period in 1992,
I got a little information

00:16:40.860 --> 00:16:46.100
about the way you left
Bosnia and Herzegovina.

00:16:46.380 --> 00:16:50.820
Tell us more about that journey
and how it all unfolded.

00:16:51.260 --> 00:16:56.820
And what is it that made
you continue to play sports?

00:16:58.060 --> 00:17:02.540
Because of everything that happened,
it was unlikely that you would

00:17:02.780 --> 00:17:08.940
continue playing sports, especially
tennis, which is quite demanding.

00:17:12.460 --> 00:17:17.900
Yes. Banja Luka was completely sealed
off, with barricades all around.

00:17:18.220 --> 00:17:21.300
We lived on the outskirts
of Banja Luka, and at one point,

00:17:21.540 --> 00:17:25.860
we weren't even able to enter it,
meaning I couldn't train anymore.

00:17:27.860 --> 00:17:32.300
My parents never talked about this,
and they probably never will,

00:17:32.580 --> 00:17:39.420
but at one point, they decided
it was safer and better for us to leave

00:17:39.740 --> 00:17:45.620
because it became unsafe. You'll
have to ask my father for the details.

00:17:46.660 --> 00:17:50.580
As a kid, I didn't understand anything.

00:17:51.860 --> 00:17:55.580
However, I felt the tension,
and I felt the fear.

00:17:57.180 --> 00:18:02.900
We will leave it at that...
The only way to leave Banja Luka

00:18:03.380 --> 00:18:09.260
was with Caritas, by the humanitarian
aircraft that flew from Banja Luka

00:18:09.460 --> 00:18:16.500
to Belgrade. I was on that aircraft
with my late mother and my brother.

00:18:16.940 --> 00:18:23.540
The other men obviously couldn't join
us. -They couldn't leave the country.

00:18:23.980 --> 00:18:27.620
They couldn't leave the country or show
up anywhere. We flew to Belgrade,

00:18:27.860 --> 00:18:31.740
and from there, we took a bus
through Hungary and Slovenia to get

00:18:31.980 --> 00:18:39.380
to a refugee center in Opatija. We were
there for 6 months. That was the summer,

00:18:39.780 --> 00:18:45.620
from May to autumn of 1992. -How old
were you at the time? -I was 13.

00:18:46.020 --> 00:18:50.220
The only message
my father left us was:

00:18:51.140 --> 00:18:54.300
"Try to make sure Ivan
keeps playing tennis."

00:18:55.020 --> 00:18:58.660
That meant by any means possible.
We literally just had plastic bags

00:18:58.860 --> 00:19:02.140
and a backpack, and I had rackets
over my shoulders when we left.

00:19:02.380 --> 00:19:06.700
We planned to come back,
just like any struggling refugee.

00:19:06.940 --> 00:19:10.300
You think everything will
pass soon and you can return,

00:19:10.540 --> 00:19:15.580
but as often the case is, you never do.
-You did come back last year.

00:19:15.780 --> 00:19:22.940
Yes. I meant it differently. Anyway,
in Opatija, I went to the tennis club

00:19:23.220 --> 00:19:30.660
"Opatija" and told everyone: "Listen,
I can play tennis. I have no money,

00:19:30.940 --> 00:19:35.980
but if you need a fourth player for
pairs or something of the sort,

00:19:36.260 --> 00:19:39.900
count me in.
I'm here if you need me."

00:19:40.140 --> 00:19:43.460
That's how I continued
playing that summer.

00:19:44.380 --> 00:19:48.940
There was a boy from Vukovar
in the same position as me,

00:19:49.140 --> 00:19:54.380
and we'd get to play when the courts
weren't occupied. We'd play for a bit,

00:19:54.620 --> 00:19:59.340
which was all for that summer.
In the end, we were kicked out

00:19:59.580 --> 00:20:03.900
of the refugee center because
there was no more space for refugees,

00:20:04.100 --> 00:20:06.700
just for the internally
displaced persons.

00:20:06.940 --> 00:20:10.020
I assume you know the difference
between these two things.

00:20:10.540 --> 00:20:15.060
We had to find accommodation
using the little money we had.

00:20:15.380 --> 00:20:19.820
This was when we realized
the situation was unsustainale,

00:20:20.260 --> 00:20:25.660
and we agreed with a Serbian family
to exchange properties.

00:20:25.980 --> 00:20:28.900
Our house, land, and everything
we had back in Banja Luka were

00:20:29.220 --> 00:20:32.780
traded for a small apartment in Rijeka.
That's how I ended up in Rijeka.

00:20:33.820 --> 00:20:38.620
It was a small two-bedroom apartment,
but it was enough for us to be able

00:20:39.060 --> 00:20:45.340
to live and survive. Then, in November
of that year, my father managed

00:20:45.620 --> 00:20:50.460
to escape with Caritas,
and our family finally reunited.

00:20:50.780 --> 00:20:53.140
We didn't know what was happening
with him prior to this.

00:20:53.420 --> 00:20:57.980
How long was your dad gone? -Around
seven months. But we didn't have phones.

00:20:58.220 --> 00:21:01.700
Was it possible for you to
focus on the sport at the time?

00:21:01.900 --> 00:21:04.860
Were you unsure of everything?
-No, the focus wasn't on the sport.

00:21:05.180 --> 00:21:08.500
The focus was on living day by day.
-Focused on surviving. -Yes.

00:21:08.740 --> 00:21:12.060
In September, I went back to school
in Opatija for a few weeks,

00:21:12.260 --> 00:21:17.540
and that was one of the more traumatic
periods. There was a lot of bullying,

00:21:17.780 --> 00:21:21.900
and the kids sadly didn't have
any empathy for refugees and

00:21:22.140 --> 00:21:26.420
internally displaced persons. It was
very ugly. But it got a lot better

00:21:26.700 --> 00:21:30.100
when I moved to Rijeka,
where I would later meet my wife.

00:21:30.340 --> 00:21:35.500
However, my father got out,
and I got a call from Italy

00:21:35.740 --> 00:21:38.020
at the beginning of 1993.

00:21:38.300 --> 00:21:42.420
I went to Italy, and as they say,
the rest is history.

00:21:42.860 --> 00:21:49.860
That's my connection to Rijeka, Croatia,
and that way of life. But looking back,

00:21:50.060 --> 00:21:55.020
I always say I feel sorry
for my parents, my grandparents,

00:21:55.220 --> 00:21:58.620
and everyone who understood
what was happening then.

00:21:58.860 --> 00:22:01.420
As children, we had no clue
what was really going on.

00:22:01.620 --> 00:22:04.700
I can't talk to you about
"My traumas..." and so forth...

00:22:04.900 --> 00:22:08.060
You're probably carrying it,
but back then, you didn't understand.

00:22:08.260 --> 00:22:11.540
You don't know it, and honestly, it's
best you don't know certain things.

00:22:11.740 --> 00:22:15.497
You keep moving forward.
-Life goes on.

00:22:15.670 --> 00:22:18.506
You climb the steps of life.
You don't even think about it.

00:22:18.893 --> 00:22:21.677
But I feel the saddest
for my grandparents.

00:22:23.445 --> 00:22:26.154
My grandmother, for example,
passed away in St Louis.

00:22:26.296 --> 00:22:29.872
Do I need to say anything more?
That's the saddest part.

00:22:30.086 --> 00:22:34.966
A person who grew up in Bosnia,
who didn't leave it all her life,

00:22:35.620 --> 00:22:41.260
passes away in St Louis, and her
cemetery is the way it is there.

00:22:41.500 --> 00:22:45.085
That's the saddest part. As kids, we'll
figure it out, all young people do,

00:22:45.202 --> 00:22:48.963
and that's the least of our problems. I
have always felt sorry for older people.

00:22:54.140 --> 00:22:58.140
What kept you going during
your years as a refugee in Rijeka?

00:22:58.580 --> 00:23:02.940
What did you, Ivan Ljubičić,
tell yourself to make it through?

00:23:03.300 --> 00:23:08.843
Tennis and sports. Tennis is the thing
that... -That gave you something...

00:23:09.080 --> 00:23:12.999
It gave you the chance to think about
tomorrow, and not about yesterday.

00:23:13.620 --> 00:23:18.660
And I've met a lot of people who,
to this day, think about the 90s

00:23:19.020 --> 00:23:23.460
and listen to the music of that time,
they're stuck there.

00:23:23.700 --> 00:23:29.180
They never managed to say,
"Okay, let's move on."

00:23:29.500 --> 00:23:33.700
I somehow managed to move on, maybe
because my life was taking me there,

00:23:33.900 --> 00:23:37.900
maybe it's the way my character is.
I was never looking back.

00:23:38.100 --> 00:23:41.500
I still like to listen to that old music
and remember moments from the past,

00:23:41.740 --> 00:23:46.900
but I live in the present and think
about tomorrow. That's my lifestyle.

00:23:47.100 --> 00:23:50.620
Back then, it was all about thinking of
the next tournament, training session,

00:23:50.860 --> 00:23:54.900
and the next step. You were always
thinking about how to be better

00:23:55.140 --> 00:24:01.420
and stronger. I was absolutely aware
that I was my family's only hope.

00:24:01.700 --> 00:24:07.300
From a very early age, I became
aware of the pressure and opportunities

00:24:07.734 --> 00:24:11.814
that tennis could bring.
Even today, when my parents say,

00:24:12.140 --> 00:24:16.020
"Don't put pressure on your kids,"
listen, you should put pressure.

00:24:16.220 --> 00:24:18.340
Being number 1
in the world is not easy,

00:24:18.580 --> 00:24:21.060
but being in the top 10 in the world
in anything is not easy.

00:24:21.300 --> 00:24:25.180
If you can't handle pressure, it's
better to go and do something else.

00:24:26.860 --> 00:24:31.500
Let's move on to 1999,
my apologies 1996.

00:24:33.020 --> 00:24:37.100
That's the beginning of your
professional career. -Correct.

00:24:37.340 --> 00:24:40.980
That's when the world found out
about you. The junior Wimbledon.

00:24:41.180 --> 00:24:45.700
Describe these beginnings to us.
I'm told there were issues with the

00:24:45.900 --> 00:24:50.296
uniforms in one of the key matches.
-Yes, a lot was going on.

00:24:52.382 --> 00:25:00.617
In that year everything happened so
quickly. There were signs during 1995.

00:25:01.700 --> 00:25:06.300
Ivo Karlović and I won
the European indoors championship,

00:25:06.500 --> 00:25:11.020
we became European champions,
which was a big surprise.

00:25:11.220 --> 00:25:15.140
We were not the favorites to win.
However, Ivo Karlović was known

00:25:15.380 --> 00:25:19.700
for his serve, and I was known for mine.
We surprised those kids there.

00:25:20.340 --> 00:25:23.060
We managed to win the championship,
which was a big shock.

00:25:23.260 --> 00:25:26.300
It was the first time
people even considered

00:25:26.460 --> 00:25:28.780
that we could start playing seriously.

00:25:29.060 --> 00:25:35.500
Then, in 1996, when I was 17, I started
playing junior tournaments in Italy.

00:25:35.900 --> 00:25:41.380
I won a match, I won two matches, I won
Firenze, Salsomaggiore, Santa Croce...

00:25:41.580 --> 00:25:45.340
Things started happening, and I won
a tournament in Prat near Firenze,

00:25:45.540 --> 00:25:48.540
which also came as a surprise.
Everything was happening in a span

00:25:48.780 --> 00:25:54.405
of 3 months, but it was happening so
quickly that I didn't get a chance

00:25:54.751 --> 00:25:57.241
to sit down and process it all.

00:25:57.626 --> 00:26:02.561
I went from a player who plays junior
tournaments to a Wimbledon player

00:26:02.900 --> 00:26:07.340
within 2 months. It was a shock
for me, and everyone around me.

00:26:07.540 --> 00:26:14.180
Suddenly, sponsors and managers showed
up. Everything just exploded all at once

00:26:14.420 --> 00:26:17.580
and my life completely changed.
The Wimbledon match in 1996,

00:26:17.780 --> 00:26:23.540
which Sky acquired the rights to
broadcast, I let my son watch in.

00:26:23.780 --> 00:26:30.020
It was also my first time seeing it,
and it was fascinating.

00:26:30.220 --> 00:26:34.180
There was that uniform. I had a
headscarf, and I also had hair.

00:26:34.420 --> 00:26:37.820
That's what I wanted to ask you about...
If you had hair back then...

00:26:38.020 --> 00:26:43.100
Yes, I had a lot of hair. I was starting
to lose it though... I was bald at 21.

00:26:43.980 --> 00:26:47.980
So those were the last attempts at
having something on my head.

00:26:49.300 --> 00:26:52.940
It seemed like grass would be
your preferred surface in those

00:26:53.220 --> 00:26:58.540
starting years but in the end...
-I have one title. I accidentally

00:26:58.900 --> 00:27:01.580
stole it from somewhere...
-So, all of your awards were stolen.

00:27:01.820 --> 00:27:05.780
The grass is horrible. Yes, in the
beginning it was my absolute favorite.

00:27:06.260 --> 00:27:11.740
Juniors Wimbledon finale was played
on it. However, I can't play on grass.

00:27:11.980 --> 00:27:15.540
In the end I won Wimbledon
as a coach, but as a player...

00:27:15.740 --> 00:27:20.900
I won one tournament on grass,
but I don't know how it happened.

00:27:21.180 --> 00:27:25.340
Grass just did not mesh well with me,
to this day I still don't know why.

00:27:25.580 --> 00:27:30.900
But by all the metrics it should.
-Yes, but the ball slips and you can't

00:27:31.140 --> 00:27:35.340
do anything about it. My serve is
less "deadly" on the grass compared to

00:27:35.540 --> 00:27:39.740
other surfaces which I don't know why,
to this day and with all my knowledge

00:27:39.940 --> 00:27:42.380
of tennis I still don't know why.

00:27:42.620 --> 00:27:47.020
I couldn't find my footing on the grass.
As a junior it worked for me,

00:27:47.260 --> 00:27:50.260
and as a coach as well, but as a
professional it didn't suit me at all.

00:27:50.660 --> 00:27:57.546
1996 was a turning point. Up until then
you were a half-professional player...

00:27:57.729 --> 00:28:01.710
Yes. -...you didn't have any resources.
But then it started becoming serious.

00:28:01.900 --> 00:28:07.900
Who were the people, or rather who was
the man, who put you on the right path?

00:28:08.340 --> 00:28:11.155
Is this when professional
management came about? -Yes.

00:28:11.252 --> 00:28:13.334
Was there a serious coach,
or was it still...

00:28:13.917 --> 00:28:21.395
I signed my first professional
sponsorship in 1996 with Adidas,

00:28:21.587 --> 00:28:25.653
a great contract even by today's
standards. I suppose they saw

00:28:26.426 --> 00:28:32.858
the next Ivanišević in me, or something
like that. That helped me a lot.

00:28:34.980 --> 00:28:39.460
In 1997, I got a call from Riccardo
Piatti asking me to work with him.

00:28:39.940 --> 00:28:46.460
All of that happened within those
6 to 9 months, and that was the solution

00:28:46.740 --> 00:28:53.140
to my entire career. Riccardo Piatti was
with me throughout my entire career.

00:28:53.620 --> 00:28:57.580
He didn't charge me for the coaching
at first. He told me I could pay him

00:28:57.780 --> 00:29:02.380
once I had the money,
which was what ended up happening.

00:29:02.620 --> 00:29:07.700
My manager at the time wasn't
the one who handled my career.

00:29:08.220 --> 00:29:11.060
He handled the contracts
and the sponsors,

00:29:11.340 --> 00:29:14.740
but Riccardo Piatti was the one who
took care of my career starting in 1997.

00:29:17.540 --> 00:29:21.860
That was the beginning
of my professional career.

00:29:22.140 --> 00:29:27.380
Later, it took me 2 years
to figure out how Riccardo operated,

00:29:27.660 --> 00:29:29.900
his way of work,
thinking, and playing style.

00:29:30.140 --> 00:29:36.340
I had to change my style of playing.
Until 1997, I was a serve-and-volley,

00:29:36.860 --> 00:29:40.820
serve-and-net player, and I was doing
drop shots and rhythm-breaking tactics.

00:29:41.100 --> 00:29:44.620
But on my first day with Riccardo,
he told me: "Look, what you're doing

00:29:44.860 --> 00:29:48.580
is nice and all, but that isn't the
future of tennis. Let's work on getting

00:29:48.860 --> 00:29:51.740
the ball over the net 700 times
without making a mistake."

00:29:51.980 --> 00:29:55.980
This was a huge change for me. It took
me 2 years to get accustomed to it all

00:29:56.260 --> 00:29:59.620
and for things to settle - what I knew
previously and what he wanted from me.

00:29:59.820 --> 00:30:03.460
In 1999, I managed to crack it.

00:30:08.180 --> 00:30:12.620
And in 2001, it all came together,
and it was your first serious title.

00:30:12.900 --> 00:30:20.180
I assume it was also the first time
you earned serious money.

00:30:21.100 --> 00:30:26.140
It happened in Lyon. -Yes.
-You got in with the elites.

00:30:26.460 --> 00:30:30.260
Was this the moment
when you realized you've made it?

00:30:30.500 --> 00:30:35.020
First, it was the junior tournament
in 1996, and in 2001, it was the first

00:30:35.260 --> 00:30:38.620
serious tournament, the first serious
money. Is that when it all came together

00:30:38.860 --> 00:30:43.500
and settled into place? -Well, 1999
was the year I made it to the top 100.

00:30:43.700 --> 00:30:46.820
In tennis, when you make it to the
top 100, it means you're participating

00:30:47.100 --> 00:30:51.020
in the main Grand Slam tournaments,
where the money is... Well, back then,

00:30:51.220 --> 00:30:56.506
the amount of money wasn't what it is
today. The prize money skyrocketed.

00:30:56.687 --> 00:31:00.740
It meant that you were a part of the
elites. That's when you start making

00:31:01.070 --> 00:31:04.951
the real money. The 2001 Lyon title
was an important step in my career.

00:31:05.296 --> 00:31:12.946
I wouldn't say it was a turning point,
but I did feel a weight drop from my

00:31:14.008 --> 00:31:19.501
shoulders once I got the title,
so I can continue evolving.

00:31:19.794 --> 00:31:29.512
I wouldn't win a title until 2005, but
overall, the 2001 title was lovely one.

00:31:31.380 --> 00:31:35.180
In 2001, I remember before the finals,
against Younes El Aynaoui,

00:31:35.420 --> 00:31:38.220
I was in the locker room,
and I had a cellphone with me.

00:31:38.420 --> 00:31:41.020
That was around the time
mobile phones became popular,

00:31:41.220 --> 00:31:45.360
and I was talking to my father about
the pressure and he bluntly told me:

00:31:45.700 --> 00:31:50.100
"We have been working on this your whole
life, so do with that what you will."

00:31:50.820 --> 00:31:53.140
No pressure at all.
-No pressure at all.

00:31:53.460 --> 00:31:56.860
The point is, I played one of
the best matches in my career 6-3 6-2.

00:31:57.100 --> 00:32:00.660
I was truly in the zone and I spent
a lot of years afterward trying to

00:32:00.900 --> 00:32:04.020
get back to that feeling, not even
the score but the zone I was in

00:32:04.260 --> 00:32:08.140
during that match and I couldn't
for a very long time.

00:32:08.620 --> 00:32:13.340
I was in a trans back then.
-And what about the negative side?

00:32:13.900 --> 00:32:16.860
Given that the show is called
Champion's Failure.

00:32:17.140 --> 00:32:21.420
One of the harder losses was in
Australia in 2002. -Do I have to?

00:32:21.620 --> 00:32:27.140
Do I have to go there? -I don't know if
it was... Let's clarify it a bit.

00:32:27.460 --> 00:32:32.420
But really when I was looking at it 2-0
and then 5-2. How did it happen? How?

00:32:33.300 --> 00:32:37.140
Well, it's stupid to say it now, I did
lose matches where I had the match ball.

00:32:37.380 --> 00:32:43.340
Because when you're a player it can just
happen. That match was the hardest match

00:32:43.580 --> 00:32:49.620
of my career, mentally and physically,
and by all measures, that match will

00:32:50.100 --> 00:32:56.500
go into, well I mean it already is,
in the book of my darkest moments.

00:32:59.340 --> 00:33:04.060
I'll try to explain what I remember,
and how we got to that point.

00:33:05.340 --> 00:33:11.700
It was the 3rd round, and it was natural
for me to be there, given my ranking.

00:33:11.980 --> 00:33:15.020
I was among the first 50 players.
I was playing against Wayne Ferreira,

00:33:15.260 --> 00:33:18.420
who was an experienced player. I
remember my coach always telling me

00:33:18.700 --> 00:33:21.460
I must look out for him
because he was winning big time,

00:33:21.700 --> 00:33:26.860
he was a big player, and all that.
In the first set, I won by 6-4.

00:33:27.780 --> 00:33:30.820
I always remember the feeling
and that feeling was:

00:33:31.020 --> 00:33:33.940
"I won the set,
but I don't think I deserved to."

00:33:34.223 --> 00:33:37.408
The second set was 6-4. I'm thinking
to myself, I'm leading 2-0 in sets.

00:33:37.580 --> 00:33:39.978
I'm not at all the better player,
but okay, whatever.

00:33:40.467 --> 00:33:45.775
His morale kind of starts going down.
The score was 5-1 or maybe even 5-2.

00:33:46.135 --> 00:33:49.295
But by the middle of the 3rd set
I started cramping up.

00:33:49.598 --> 00:33:52.564
There are various types of cramps, the
ones with which you can keep playing

00:33:52.861 --> 00:33:56.016
and those with which you can't.
I think these were in my calves.

00:33:58.580 --> 00:34:01.860
The score was 5-3, 40-15,
two match balls for me.

00:34:02.264 --> 00:34:04.583
We were practically there,
but I couldn't serve.

00:34:04.774 --> 00:34:06.854
The cramps were maybe even
in my abdominal muscles,

00:34:06.976 --> 00:34:09.763
which are the absolute worst kind,
because you really can't do anything.

00:34:10.001 --> 00:34:13.193
5-4. 5-5, I lose the third set,
as well as the fourth.

00:34:13.438 --> 00:34:16.838
It's the middle of the day,
the heat is unbearable.

00:34:18.540 --> 00:34:24.740
The sun sets, the weather gets
a little better, but I'm losing

00:34:25.020 --> 00:34:29.940
in the 5th set break, 3-2, 4-2, 5-2
he leads in the fifth set.

00:34:30.180 --> 00:34:34.260
When everyone thought it was over,
I somehow find new strength.

00:34:34.860 --> 00:34:39.100
There's no more sun, it's cooler.
5-3, 5-4, 5-5.

00:34:39.300 --> 00:34:41.300
I'm coming back in the 5th set.

00:34:41.500 --> 00:34:46.093
At 5-5, I hit the ball
and the blister I had bursts.

00:34:46.468 --> 00:34:50.220
I literally can't
hold the racket anymore.

00:34:50.460 --> 00:34:52.260
I call the physiotherapist.

00:34:52.500 --> 00:34:54.740
Everyone who has played tennis
and had blisters knows

00:34:54.940 --> 00:34:58.020
that you can bandage
all blisters on your hand,

00:34:58.260 --> 00:35:01.820
except on the palm. If it's on
the palm, no one can help you.

00:35:02.020 --> 00:35:06.220
You either bandage the entire palm,
but then you lose the feeling.

00:35:06.420 --> 00:35:09.780
That’s how it was.
In the end, I lost 7-5.

00:35:10.140 --> 00:35:13.820
That will forever remain
the most painful loss because,

00:35:14.020 --> 00:35:16.500
if I remember correctly,
in the fourth round

00:35:16.700 --> 00:35:19.380
I was supposed to play against
Albert Costa, who was a great player.

00:35:19.540 --> 00:35:24.852
But on that fast surface... I think
Ferreira played the semifinals that year.

00:35:25.254 --> 00:35:29.168
It wasn’t just a big loss,
but also a missed big opportunity.

00:35:29.710 --> 00:35:33.289
I won’t exaggerate if I say
that my career was not decided,

00:35:35.641 --> 00:35:41.598
but definitely took a certain
direction after that match.

00:35:42.175 --> 00:35:45.839
Maybe things could have been
better if I had won that match.

00:35:46.380 --> 00:35:53.220
How did you recover and get
back on the winning path?

00:35:53.500 --> 00:35:57.980
I didn’t for a while, because
it was in 2002, 2003, and 2004.

00:35:58.380 --> 00:36:03.340
I didn’t win anything. Until the 2004
Olympics when we last saw each other.

00:36:04.220 --> 00:36:08.500
That year was... The medal...

00:36:08.820 --> 00:36:11.220
That's when you made your
comeback. -I came back.

00:36:11.420 --> 00:36:15.380
I started to believe again
that there was something in me

00:36:15.620 --> 00:36:19.540
strong enough that I could
rise above mediocrity.

00:36:22.780 --> 00:36:26.700
Let’s be clear, I was ranked
between 25th and 45th.

00:36:27.020 --> 00:36:29.660
For me, that was average.
I wanted more.

00:36:30.020 --> 00:36:38.180
I’d be lying if I said that match
didn’t... Slow me down.

00:36:39.340 --> 00:36:42.220
It shook my confidence.

00:36:42.540 --> 00:36:45.700
Until 2004, when the medal
brought me back.

00:36:45.980 --> 00:36:52.220
I got my wings back again.
At the end of that year, I got married.

00:36:52.580 --> 00:36:56.620
That gave me a lot of personal
security... -Calmness.

00:36:57.340 --> 00:37:02.740
Then 2005 and 2006 were absolute
tennis rhapsody years in my career.

00:37:03.260 --> 00:37:09.300
We’ll forget the sad period.
Let’s start from Athens 2004.

00:37:09.500 --> 00:37:17.976
Our famous celebration. Then we go
to 2010, when there was perfection

00:37:18.414 --> 00:37:24.826
in terms of winning tournaments,
the national team, Davis Cup,

00:37:26.439 --> 00:37:33.309
Olympic bronze. A perfect streak.
How much did that bronze help?

00:37:33.616 --> 00:37:38.816
That was the foundation
for understanding where you were.

00:37:39.220 --> 00:37:43.660
The bronze was the foundation
of all later successes.

00:37:44.140 --> 00:37:47.013
Not just because it was
an Olympic bronze,

00:37:47.172 --> 00:37:49.206
of course, that’s important,

00:37:49.477 --> 00:37:53.942
but also the matches we won
and the way we won them.

00:37:54.361 --> 00:37:57.502
We beat great teams.
Mario Ančić and I defeated

00:37:57.820 --> 00:38:01.300
all the best doubles pairs in
the world at that tournament.

00:38:01.500 --> 00:38:05.540
That helped us in 2005
when we won the Davis Cup.

00:38:05.780 --> 00:38:09.940
We beat the Bryan brothers,
the greatest players of all time.

00:38:11.260 --> 00:38:16.060
Athens is the foundation of all my
successes that followed.

00:38:16.340 --> 00:38:20.980
You know yourself that
the atmosphere was phenomenal.

00:38:21.260 --> 00:38:26.060
We had a great time.
The Olympic village is hard to explain

00:38:26.340 --> 00:38:30.820
to someone who hasn’t been there.
The cheering, the other sports.

00:38:31.060 --> 00:38:34.180
We go to your games,
you come to our matches.

00:38:34.780 --> 00:38:43.320
It was wonderful. Sydney 2000
was a bit of a tourist trip.

00:38:43.656 --> 00:38:48.086
Your first Olympics, you're a bit lost.
At the second one, you go all the way.

00:38:48.303 --> 00:38:52.320
That’s what I needed for
everything that happened after.

00:38:52.595 --> 00:38:56.454
And the cherry
on top after that.

00:39:03.100 --> 00:39:07.620
After the bronze,
came that famous trophy.

00:39:08.220 --> 00:39:12.580
Davis Cup 2005. We played
in the final against Slovakia.

00:39:12.820 --> 00:39:15.340
For the first time
in tennis history, two teams

00:39:15.540 --> 00:39:18.180
that weren’t seeded
made it to the Davis Cup final.

00:39:18.420 --> 00:39:21.300
We beat the Americans in
a match that’s still talked about today.

00:39:21.500 --> 00:39:23.940
Roddick, Agassi,
the Bryan brothers.

00:39:24.260 --> 00:39:27.660
Two matches in Split
against Romania and Russia.

00:39:28.020 --> 00:39:32.140
Every time I mention
Split 2005, I get chills.

00:39:32.460 --> 00:39:37.700
The atmosphere was unreal. Whoever
showed up, we would have beaten them.

00:39:38.180 --> 00:39:40.780
In Split, no one had a chance.

00:39:40.980 --> 00:39:43.620
And the final against
Slovakia in Bratislava.

00:39:43.900 --> 00:39:46.260
After the first day,
we were leading 2-1.

00:39:46.500 --> 00:39:51.137
That Sunday I woke up...
-Your neck was stiff.

00:39:52.962 --> 00:39:55.988
I played on tablets,
with a painkiller injection.

00:39:56.247 --> 00:40:01.074
In the end, I lost,
but Mario won.

00:40:02.420 --> 00:40:05.260
The reception in
Zagreb was phenomenal.

00:40:05.500 --> 00:40:09.020
They say there were
70, 80 thousand people.

00:40:09.220 --> 00:40:13.220
I remember the bus ride
from the airport to the square.

00:40:13.420 --> 00:40:16.980
I thought no one would
show up for the reception.

00:40:17.180 --> 00:40:21.980
That’s every athlete’s fear.
-I thought the same.

00:40:22.220 --> 00:40:25.380
But, when you arrive
and see the people...

00:40:25.780 --> 00:40:28.060
You realize what
you’ve done. -Exactly.

00:40:28.340 --> 00:40:35.340
Especially you, who are 250-300
days abroad and traveling.

00:40:35.700 --> 00:40:42.820
It is important for the national team
to feel that... -Yes.

00:40:43.500 --> 00:40:49.420
Calling all people and fans.
When the reception is made, come.

00:40:49.700 --> 00:40:56.676
It means a lot to athletes. All
of us athletes are in tunnels,

00:40:57.300 --> 00:41:02.540
in rooms, lonely. It is not a
luxurious life as people think.

00:41:03.420 --> 00:41:10.093
When something like that happens,
when we "die" for the national team

00:41:10.431 --> 00:41:13.111
and when it is celebrated,
let it be celebrated.

00:41:13.240 --> 00:41:15.264
It gives you the purpose in life.

00:41:15.440 --> 00:41:17.733
We need to let people know
that we appreciate them,

00:41:17.921 --> 00:41:20.749
we watch them on TV,
on iPads, iPhones,

00:41:20.986 --> 00:41:24.826
but when we have the opportunity
to show respect for athletes,

00:41:24.996 --> 00:41:30.296
then do it right. That is very
important. -Nicely said, I agree.

00:41:32.500 --> 00:41:38.020
Year 2006, Roland Garros,
semi-finals, right? -That's right.

00:41:38.820 --> 00:41:41.980
Where are we there?
-We are at the top.

00:41:42.460 --> 00:41:44.980
I am the third player in the world,
I've never been better,

00:41:45.180 --> 00:41:47.740
I'm playing the best
tennis of my life.

00:41:47.980 --> 00:41:50.260
But, at Roland Garros
against Nadal.

00:41:50.540 --> 00:41:53.380
There can be a period
at the end of that sentence.

00:41:53.580 --> 00:41:57.020
That was the maximum. There was
no room to step forward? -No.

00:41:57.380 --> 00:42:01.660
Maybe there was space in 2006 in
Australia, at the beginning of the year.

00:42:02.020 --> 00:42:07.500
Back up a bit. We win the Davis
Cup in 2005, I go to India without

00:42:07.780 --> 00:42:12.860
training, I win the tournament,
I beat Carlos S. in the final,

00:42:13.100 --> 00:42:17.100
I come to Melbourne as one of
the favorites to win the tournament.

00:42:17.540 --> 00:42:21.700
I'm ranked 5-6, but everyone
is already making predictions.

00:42:21.940 --> 00:42:25.860
I am among the best in terms
of form and what I can do.

00:42:26.260 --> 00:42:29.540
I easily win all matches.
In the quarter finals I lost to

00:42:29.900 --> 00:42:35.340
Marcos Baghdatis. The match I
was losing 2-0, I came back to 2-2,

00:42:35.620 --> 00:42:38.700
I had a chance in the
fifth set and I didn't take it.

00:42:38.900 --> 00:42:42.300
If we are talking about winning
the Grand Slam,

00:42:42.500 --> 00:42:45.980
it was Australia,
not Roland Garros.

00:42:46.260 --> 00:42:48.620
Despite being in the
semifinals of Roland Garros,

00:42:48.860 --> 00:42:51.380
against Nadal on clay,
I had two set points

00:42:51.580 --> 00:42:57.220
in the third set, but objectively...
I would just postpone inevitable.

00:42:57.780 --> 00:43:04.573
The only thing I didn't play at the end
of my career was the Grand Slam final

00:43:04.995 --> 00:43:11.500
or did I win it. -And in 2010,
you won the Masters as the oldest.

00:43:11.740 --> 00:43:17.020
At what age? -Now these young people
are pushing those boundaries.

00:43:17.180 --> 00:43:22.300
It was a big surprise then.
-All of those who played then...

00:43:22.540 --> 00:43:27.140
Roger slipped away, but I
beat Đoković, Nadal, Roddick...

00:43:27.420 --> 00:43:29.820
Everybody in that tournament.
-Everybody. Everything matched.

00:43:30.020 --> 00:43:33.380
What happened then? Then you
probably said that's it. -I did.

00:43:33.502 --> 00:43:35.995
That was the beginning
of the end. -In your head?

00:43:36.147 --> 00:43:38.107
The beginning
of the end in the head.

00:43:38.270 --> 00:43:42.791
In 2011, I was already thinking
about the end of my career.

00:43:43.100 --> 00:43:48.565
Roger friendly persuaded
me to play one more year.

00:43:51.940 --> 00:43:57.620
That was the culmination.
-Why? -Why did I stop playing?

00:43:57.820 --> 00:44:03.180
Why did you stop relatively early?
Were there any health problems?

00:44:03.380 --> 00:44:08.220
Or psyche? -I had problems,
and still have them, with ankles.

00:44:08.700 --> 00:44:13.700
They told me that they couldn't
help the cartilage in my ankle.

00:44:13.900 --> 00:44:18.540
A few injections helped,
but that's not a solution.

00:44:18.820 --> 00:44:25.420
I realized that the best tennis
is behind me, not in front of me.

00:44:26.140 --> 00:44:29.700
A second child was born.
Zara joined us.

00:44:30.100 --> 00:44:33.540
Traveling with two small
children is not very easy.

00:44:34.300 --> 00:44:38.220
Everything somehow
came together in one pile.

00:44:38.460 --> 00:44:41.220
I remember like it was
yesterday, I was in Dubai.

00:44:41.420 --> 00:44:46.420
I finished the tournament.
Aida was there with the children.

00:44:46.660 --> 00:44:50.580
It was agreed that I would
go to the USA for a month.

00:44:50.860 --> 00:44:55.820
We will not take children. I'd fly to
Indian Wells, and they'd fly home.

00:44:57.060 --> 00:45:00.300
We will stay a few more
days in Dubai, then we will fly.

00:45:00.540 --> 00:45:05.540
The day before the flight,
I woke up at four in the morning

00:45:06.020 --> 00:45:11.510
and realized that it was over.
My career is over.

00:45:12.660 --> 00:45:17.060
Aida is always on the right side.
I wake her up. - That's it.

00:45:17.700 --> 00:45:23.580
She looks at me, I say it's over.
She understood immediately,

00:45:23.820 --> 00:45:26.900
she didn't even try to
persuade me. Let's talk, no.

00:45:27.078 --> 00:45:31.859
We woke up, drank coffee,
waited for the children to wake up.

00:45:32.134 --> 00:45:33.875
We get it, it's over.

00:45:34.091 --> 00:45:37.000
How to tell the coach,
when to tell the coach?

00:45:37.317 --> 00:45:42.517
That day we have two more
training sessions, and plan.

00:45:44.100 --> 00:45:47.380
We agreed that we would
invite everyone to dinner,

00:45:47.620 --> 00:45:51.500
and tell the coach and conditioning
coach that this was the decision.

00:45:51.860 --> 00:45:54.180
It was the longest day of my life.

00:45:54.420 --> 00:46:00.583
I stopped playing in my head, but
I had to do two training sessions.

00:46:01.140 --> 00:46:04.540
I remember Ricardo telling
me when we remembered,

00:46:04.780 --> 00:46:09.420
he spoke to the conditioning
coach and said I was absent.

00:46:09.660 --> 00:46:12.420
Something is wrong,
we need to animate him.

00:46:12.660 --> 00:46:15.660
The second training session
was even worse.

00:46:16.140 --> 00:46:19.220
At dinner they understood
what it was about.

00:46:19.460 --> 00:46:22.940
We decided to play another
match in Monte Carlo.

00:46:23.180 --> 00:46:28.140
If I could go back now,
I probably wouldn't play it.

00:46:28.380 --> 00:46:34.100
As my professional career
began in Monte Carlo,

00:46:34.500 --> 00:46:40.420
In 1999, I wanted to close the
whole circle, to make it the last match.

00:46:40.620 --> 00:46:45.580
That was... -2012.
-Against Ivan Dodig. -Dodig, yes.

00:46:46.380 --> 00:46:49.534
It's been 12 years.
To sum it all up.

00:46:49.764 --> 00:46:56.182
We mentioned several situations.
Is there anything you regret?

00:46:56.609 --> 00:47:00.649
I don't believe it, but...
If you could, but you didn't?

00:47:00.983 --> 00:47:03.604
Now you mentioned
about the quarterfinals.

00:47:03.836 --> 00:47:06.836
Can you believe that no one
asked me that before?

00:47:07.075 --> 00:47:08.995
Do I regret anything?

00:47:09.234 --> 00:47:13.274
I would like to play that
quarter-final against Baghdatis again.

00:47:13.411 --> 00:47:18.884
Only the fifth set? -Both the first
and the second. The ones I lost.

00:47:20.260 --> 00:47:23.340
I might want to play
with Ferreira again.

00:47:24.849 --> 00:47:29.909
Those are two defeats
that were difficult.

00:47:31.549 --> 00:47:38.125
In the end, that's life.
You learn from negative experiences.

00:47:38.776 --> 00:47:42.547
Kids do not understand
negative experiences.

00:47:42.846 --> 00:47:46.966
They are absolutely necessary
to achieve something.

00:47:47.580 --> 00:47:52.380
We build ourselves up more through
defeats than through victories.

00:47:52.620 --> 00:47:55.820
Victories are quickly forgotten.
Titles count.

00:47:56.053 --> 00:48:00.376
Defeats make us stronger
and we learn from defeats.

00:48:05.620 --> 00:48:09.380
Tennis is a specific individual sport.

00:48:10.060 --> 00:48:13.220
If you are successful,
you play for 200-300 days in a year.

00:48:13.460 --> 00:48:15.620
You don't even know
the name of your home.

00:48:15.860 --> 00:48:19.260
Tell me a little about
hanging out at tournaments.

00:48:19.500 --> 00:48:22.380
Do sincere friendships
exist among tennis players?

00:48:22.620 --> 00:48:29.820
My theory. About Nadal,
Đoković and Federer.

00:48:30.160 --> 00:48:33.800
No one counts the Grand Slams,
nothing matters to anyone.

00:48:34.056 --> 00:48:37.713
In fact, everything is important to
everyone. Everyone wants to be the best.

00:48:38.039 --> 00:48:41.639
Is it the same in that
personal friendship?

00:48:42.100 --> 00:48:45.980
Is there sincerity or
is it classic interest?

00:48:48.260 --> 00:48:52.860
A tennis player travels
42, 43, 45 weeks a year.

00:48:53.540 --> 00:48:58.060
In those weeks, you see
mostly the same people.

00:48:58.700 --> 00:49:02.780
You spend more time with your
opponents than with your family.

00:49:03.300 --> 00:49:04.740
That's a fact.

00:49:04.980 --> 00:49:08.984
In the end, it is clear that
there are true friendships.

00:49:10.203 --> 00:49:13.860
It's hard to play against friends.
It's not simple.

00:49:15.609 --> 00:49:21.980
There are also those you
don't want to see. It's so natural.

00:49:23.580 --> 00:49:28.900
If we talk about this trio,
Federer and Nadal are...

00:49:31.580 --> 00:49:37.940
In fact, everything starts with respect.
Novak recently spoke about that.

00:49:38.180 --> 00:49:44.460
They respect each other very much.
They understand themselves.

00:49:44.940 --> 00:49:48.740
Only they can understand
what they are going through.

00:49:48.980 --> 00:49:52.380
We, mere mortals, cannot
understand what it means to win

00:49:52.580 --> 00:49:56.260
20 Grand Slam titles and
what they have to go through.

00:49:56.540 --> 00:49:59.940
They respect each other
and understand each other.

00:50:00.180 --> 00:50:05.940
On a personal level, perhaps
one fits more than the other.

00:50:06.260 --> 00:50:11.060
I know that Roger and
Rafa went to dinners.

00:50:11.380 --> 00:50:14.940
They don't have a problem.
We come to that over time,

00:50:15.140 --> 00:50:17.340
not from the first day.

00:50:17.540 --> 00:50:20.660
It is a relationship
that develops over time.

00:50:20.900 --> 00:50:23.540
I also went to dinners
with other tennis players.

00:50:23.740 --> 00:50:25.820
I played against them
the next day.

00:50:26.020 --> 00:50:33.180
We are professionals and
we play for titles, for records.

00:50:33.460 --> 00:50:38.060
The most normal thing is
that there is rivalry, which does

00:50:38.260 --> 00:50:44.060
not necessarily mean that
it is rivalry in personal life.

00:50:46.740 --> 00:50:53.620
Ljubo, different sports are valued
differently in terms of money.

00:50:53.980 --> 00:50:58.020
There are different
funds for player rewards.

00:50:58.300 --> 00:51:02.020
Do you think maybe tennis
is the most brutal in that?

00:51:02.260 --> 00:51:06.660
When you are at the tournament,
everything is paid for and organized.

00:51:06.900 --> 00:51:12.340
The moment you lose,
you lose everything. -Yes.

00:51:13.580 --> 00:51:17.140
You no longer have any fees.
They literally kick your ass.

00:51:17.420 --> 00:51:21.420
That's true, but it's
an individual sport.

00:51:21.700 --> 00:51:25.300
All that individual sport
brings, good and bad.

00:51:25.700 --> 00:51:28.039
I know a lot of football players...

00:51:28.359 --> 00:51:30.999
In football, even if you lose,
you get your monthly salary.

00:51:31.215 --> 00:51:33.415
Yes, it's like that in every
team sport, however,

00:51:33.820 --> 00:51:37.020
many football players have told me:
"I wish I had played tennis."

00:51:37.700 --> 00:51:42.130
Why? Because football players
only see the beautiful side of tennis.

00:51:42.373 --> 00:51:45.185
You choose a coach, play in the
tournaments you want,

00:51:45.314 --> 00:51:47.427
sleep in the hotel you want...

00:51:47.648 --> 00:51:50.529
It's all nice, but the fact is that
at the end of the day,

00:51:50.775 --> 00:51:54.497
if you lose you win...
If you win, you get something.

00:51:54.728 --> 00:51:59.608
You constantly, every day,
every week actually,

00:51:59.802 --> 00:52:01.442
you earn money or not,

00:52:01.697 --> 00:52:05.130
if we talk about the economic
and the sports part.

00:52:05.359 --> 00:52:08.646
You go to the tournament, and
you don't worry about anything.

00:52:08.945 --> 00:52:14.997
We called travel agencies
when we needed a plane ticket.

00:52:15.408 --> 00:52:19.248
If we were asked about the return
date, we would answer: "I don't know".

00:52:19.538 --> 00:52:21.966
It's hard to explain when
you want to book a hotel.

00:52:22.158 --> 00:52:25.513
Listen, I'd like a reservation for
ten days, and maybe I'll stay for two.

00:52:25.779 --> 00:52:28.126
How will we know?
We won't know.

00:52:28.591 --> 00:52:31.511
And the fact is that
at a higher level,

00:52:31.860 --> 00:52:37.837
the organizer pays the player
for one room and a prize fund.

00:52:37.997 --> 00:52:39.978
Does not pay travel expenses,
he does not pay for

00:52:40.136 --> 00:52:42.251
another room and of course
food is provided in the club.

00:52:42.382 --> 00:52:44.782
If you want to eat out it
will be at your own expense.

00:52:44.984 --> 00:52:47.744
So the expenses of tennis
players and their teams are huge.

00:52:47.983 --> 00:52:51.644
However, the fact is that the prize
fund has been significantly increased.

00:52:51.920 --> 00:52:54.425
Just when I stopped playing.

00:52:54.833 --> 00:52:58.667
But I must brag that I am somewhat
responsible for that,

00:52:58.936 --> 00:53:01.776
because I was politically active
during my career

00:53:01.891 --> 00:53:04.362
and a representative of the players.

00:53:04.566 --> 00:53:07.808
At the tournaments, we worked
a lot to increase the prize funds.

00:53:07.932 --> 00:53:10.652
I'm glad to see that at least
this generation after me

00:53:10.778 --> 00:53:13.105
enjoys it a little.
-Well done, Ljubo.

00:53:14.660 --> 00:53:18.140
2012. is the year
in which you ended

00:53:18.420 --> 00:53:21.780
an active career
and started another. -Yes.

00:53:22.060 --> 00:53:24.660
When did you start
thinking about that?

00:53:24.940 --> 00:53:27.140
Knowing you, I would
never have thought

00:53:27.420 --> 00:53:30.820
that you would go to
the "other side" so quickly.

00:53:31.140 --> 00:53:35.140
For the last three years
of my playing career, I contacted

00:53:35.460 --> 00:53:39.740
a company that prepares athletes
for the end of their careers.

00:53:40.100 --> 00:53:41.980
That is very important.

00:53:42.260 --> 00:53:46.780
I told all theathletes I talked to:
"Prepare for the end of your career."

00:53:47.060 --> 00:53:49.780
So, the end cannot
just happen to you.

00:53:50.060 --> 00:53:53.500
It's like going
somewhere unprepared.

00:53:53.780 --> 00:53:55.780
You have to be prepared for that.

00:53:56.060 --> 00:53:58.740
Personally, I was afraid of my
private life, because I saw

00:53:59.020 --> 00:54:02.060
a lot of athletes who got
divorced, bankrupt...

00:54:02.300 --> 00:54:04.900
I was really scared.

00:54:06.140 --> 00:54:08.260
But I was lucky
to meet that expert

00:54:08.540 --> 00:54:11.340
from Switzerland
who prepared me for it.

00:54:11.540 --> 00:54:13.860
Without going into details,
I will only say

00:54:13.966 --> 00:54:15.650
that he prepared me
mentally and financially.

00:54:15.765 --> 00:54:17.806
He actually explained
to me what the life

00:54:17.907 --> 00:54:19.758
of an athlete looks like
when his career is over.

00:54:19.885 --> 00:54:21.330
He helped me a lot.

00:54:21.442 --> 00:54:23.267
My first job after my
career was on television.

00:54:23.300 --> 00:54:24.700
On Italian Sky TV.

00:54:24.980 --> 00:54:27.380
This is the first thing that
happened to me in 2012.

00:54:27.580 --> 00:54:29.660
They contacted me because they
wanted me to come

00:54:29.860 --> 00:54:31.660
and commentate on tennis.
I was very glad,

00:54:31.940 --> 00:54:34.980
because even today,
whenever I have a time,

00:54:35.180 --> 00:54:38.900
I commentate for Sky.
It's a pleasure to do it, indeed,

00:54:39.140 --> 00:54:41.900
because I like the way
the Italians do it.

00:54:43.060 --> 00:54:47.740
And the opportunity to be a coach
appeared with the arrival

00:54:47.940 --> 00:54:51.060
of Miloš Raonić in 2013.

00:54:51.340 --> 00:54:54.460
His manager, who was also my
manager, contacted me and asked:

00:54:54.660 --> 00:54:57.770
"Ljubo, would you like
to try yourself as a coach?"

00:54:57.957 --> 00:55:00.037
They were big competition for me,
Paul Annacon

00:55:00.160 --> 00:55:03.060
former coach of Sampras
and Federer  and Brad Gilbert

00:55:03.181 --> 00:55:05.581
who was Agassi’s coach
and now coaching Coco Gauf.

00:55:05.781 --> 00:55:09.181
The three of us were in competition
and he had to choose one of us.

00:55:09.374 --> 00:55:13.574
I went to Rome, exactly one year ago,
now should be the anniversary...

00:55:13.783 --> 00:55:18.020
I spoke with Miloš there and
told him my vision of his tennis,

00:55:18.242 --> 00:55:21.832
how he should play and
what I think needs to be improved.

00:55:22.590 --> 00:55:24.830
He said to me: "Thank you,
I'll get back to you."

00:55:24.976 --> 00:55:27.136
I returned home to Monte Carlo.

00:55:27.330 --> 00:55:29.970
A week and two passed
and he didn't get back to me.

00:55:30.211 --> 00:55:33.211
and then he called me and asked:
"Can you come with me to Roland Garros,

00:55:33.885 --> 00:55:37.466
on some sort of trial
period until Wimbledon?"

00:55:37.568 --> 00:55:39.568
I replied that I could.

00:55:39.825 --> 00:55:43.599
However, doing a trial period
in the middle of the season is horrible.

00:55:43.770 --> 00:55:46.724
You don't really have time
or space to work on anything.

00:55:46.793 --> 00:55:49.356
You are there with the player,
but you can't tell him:

00:55:49.564 --> 00:55:52.124
"Let's try to change the shot,"
because you don't have time for that.

00:55:52.278 --> 00:55:54.758
I think he played the
third round of Roland Garros,

00:55:54.864 --> 00:55:57.474
the first round of Halle,
first round of Eastbourne

00:55:57.622 --> 00:55:59.382
at Wimbledon
he lost in the second round.

00:55:59.644 --> 00:56:01.404
I thought, well that's not it.

00:56:01.503 --> 00:56:04.254
After these results, there is no
chance that he will choose me.

00:56:04.413 --> 00:56:07.161
However, we agreed to discuss
everything after Wimbledon.

00:56:07.327 --> 00:56:10.327
After Wimbledon I told him:
"Miloš, I don't know

00:56:10.464 --> 00:56:13.903
what you're thinking about
and what your plans are,

00:56:14.058 --> 00:56:17.442
but I'll just tell you
that if you want me to stay,

00:56:17.612 --> 00:56:22.153
I want my fitness coach, I want you
to play the tournaments I choose

00:56:22.357 --> 00:56:26.077
and I'd like to spend every week
with you, until the end of the year."

00:56:26.340 --> 00:56:29.780
He said he agreed. That's how
our cooperation began.

00:56:29.980 --> 00:56:33.220
All credit to him for believing in me
regardless of the results.

00:56:33.335 --> 00:56:35.495
He believed in the vision,
in my commitment and

00:56:35.657 --> 00:56:41.737
in the fact that I dedicated almost
every moment of my life to him.

00:56:42.500 --> 00:56:44.540
In the end it really paid off.

00:56:44.740 --> 00:56:48.460
He placed in the top ten players that
year, and during the next two years

00:56:48.660 --> 00:56:52.180
he climbed the rankings and reached the
position of the third player in the world.

00:56:52.380 --> 00:56:57.540
It was actually a base,
a start, some guarantee for Roger,

00:56:58.300 --> 00:57:00.780
who saw that I knew my job.

00:57:00.918 --> 00:57:03.370
Despite being a former tennis player,
it didn't mean that

00:57:03.460 --> 00:57:05.260
I also knew the coaching job.

00:57:05.432 --> 00:57:09.680
Roger told me later and openly:
"I followed you and thought about you,

00:57:09.946 --> 00:57:13.460
but I wanted to see
if you were good as a coach.

00:57:13.740 --> 00:57:16.100
When I saw what you
accomplished with Raonić

00:57:16.300 --> 00:57:20.100
and when you were free,
I decided to contact you."

00:57:20.980 --> 00:57:23.820
Well done, you just
answered my next question.

00:57:23.966 --> 00:57:25.578
So this was an assist?

00:57:25.738 --> 00:57:29.498
How did the collaboration between
you and Federer come about?

00:57:29.698 --> 00:57:32.774
Tell us a little more
about that relationship.

00:57:33.160 --> 00:57:35.760
We were quite close
on a personal level,

00:57:36.060 --> 00:57:38.380
we were friends, family friends.

00:57:38.660 --> 00:57:42.140
He used to call me sometimes
and ask for some advice,

00:57:42.380 --> 00:57:46.020
for some tactics against Đoković,
against Nadal,

00:57:46.260 --> 00:57:48.180
even when we weren't work together.

00:57:48.420 --> 00:57:52.220
He also knew, as much as I know
about tennis and his game.

00:57:53.300 --> 00:57:59.060
I think I stopped working with
Miloš in October of 2015.

00:58:00.780 --> 00:58:04.660
and then I made an agreement
with Sky Italia to come

00:58:04.900 --> 00:58:09.580
to the Masters at the end of the year
and commentate on the matches.

00:58:09.860 --> 00:58:12.900
I was in constant contact
with Roger and when he heard

00:58:13.100 --> 00:58:15.260
that I was coming to London,
he said: "Let's meet one evening,

00:58:15.500 --> 00:58:19.060
and go to dinner,
you, me, Aida and Mirka.

00:58:19.380 --> 00:58:22.620
I thought it would be
a dinner like any other.

00:58:23.300 --> 00:58:27.620
At the end of that dinner
he surprised me when he said:

00:58:28.180 --> 00:58:31.140
"Would you be interested in
working with me?"

00:58:31.380 --> 00:58:32.980
It was an absolute
shock for me,

00:58:33.220 --> 00:58:35.540
but oneof the most beautiful
moments in my life.

00:58:35.780 --> 00:58:39.780
It was a huge honor for me.

00:58:40.300 --> 00:58:44.460
Of course I immediately agreed,
although we didn't talk about money at all.

00:58:44.700 --> 00:58:47.340
That was unquestionable for me.

00:58:47.540 --> 00:58:50.740
I told him how I thought
he should play.

00:58:50.980 --> 00:58:53.340
My goal is that he must
win the Grand Slam.

00:58:53.517 --> 00:58:56.317
I even said at that moment
that he must win more than one.

00:58:56.556 --> 00:58:58.796
And so it all started.

00:58:59.020 --> 00:59:03.864
It was hard at first,
because he soon got injured.

00:59:04.505 --> 00:59:07.728
The first problem
was with the knee.

00:59:08.340 --> 00:59:11.700
That 2016 was awkward,
buteverything got better after that,

00:59:11.980 --> 00:59:16.740
so that collaboration
was very, very successful.

00:59:17.660 --> 00:59:22.900
That experience with him is special,
because no matter that

00:59:23.220 --> 00:59:27.980
I both played and choached,
that level of professionalism

00:59:28.780 --> 00:59:34.300
and everything related to him
is unimaginable.

00:59:35.700 --> 00:59:39.700
What's the difference
between him and the rest of us?

00:59:39.940 --> 00:59:44.980
There is not half an hour in his
day that is not planned.

00:59:45.180 --> 00:59:48.620
That is six or nine
months in advance.

00:59:48.900 --> 00:59:52.140
So, everything must be
planned in detail.

00:59:52.392 --> 00:59:54.912
You can't tell him: "Come on, I guess
you have time for one dinner?"

00:59:55.121 --> 00:59:56.921
He doesn’t have time.

00:59:57.420 --> 01:00:00.380
Six months in advance?
-And more.

01:00:00.820 --> 01:00:04.100
Everything can be planned even
nine or 12 months in advance.

01:00:04.620 --> 01:00:07.700
If a sponsor needs
half a day of his time,

01:00:07.940 --> 01:00:10.420
then it must be planned
a year in advance.

01:00:10.660 --> 01:00:15.340
He is such a professional
who will respect everything.

01:00:15.580 --> 01:00:19.060
"I don't feel like it today",
it does not exist with him.

01:00:19.340 --> 01:00:22.580
And what is he like when he trains?
-He’s an animal.

01:00:22.860 --> 01:00:25.500
People think that
everything is easy for him.

01:00:25.686 --> 01:00:28.566
It's easy for him, because he
brought everything to perfection.

01:00:28.696 --> 01:00:31.496
We had training sessions
that lasted 7-8 hours at a time.

01:00:31.649 --> 01:00:35.929
We did preparations
and training on fields

01:00:36.233 --> 01:00:40.553
far away from the tournament venue,
far from everyone's eyes.

01:00:41.020 --> 01:00:44.348
We were constantly
looking for special conditions,

01:00:44.474 --> 01:00:46.645
isolated places,
where no one could see us,

01:00:46.844 --> 01:00:48.996
because he didn't like to show
what he was doing,

01:00:49.165 --> 01:00:50.906
how much he was doing and how.

01:00:51.517 --> 01:00:54.120
And then we would show up
at the tournament and train

01:00:54.468 --> 01:00:57.620
for about half an hour,
so everyone thought that was all,

01:00:57.832 --> 01:01:00.339
while we had training sessions
that literally lasted 7-8 hours.

01:01:00.685 --> 01:01:03.725
I was literally exhausted, because
I stood by him the whole time.

01:01:03.934 --> 01:01:07.104
Not to mention what
he was going through.

01:01:07.407 --> 01:01:10.269
But he wouldn't have
succeeded without it.

01:01:10.452 --> 01:01:13.332
And your relationship, which
had to turn from a friendly one

01:01:13.519 --> 01:01:17.214
into a business one,
a coach-player relationship,

01:01:17.362 --> 01:01:19.034
how did that work?

01:01:19.239 --> 01:01:22.331
What was it like on
an individual basis? -Relaxed.

01:01:22.690 --> 01:01:24.410
At no point were
there any tensions.

01:01:24.642 --> 01:01:28.162
There were a couple of situations
where I had to be a little tougher on him.

01:01:28.417 --> 01:01:35.120
Sometimes I felt that it should be
"tightened" a bit, because it loses focus,

01:01:35.457 --> 01:01:40.137
bring him to his senses,
to clarify his priorities,

01:01:40.463 --> 01:01:43.143
which he may have forgotten
at some point.

01:01:43.289 --> 01:01:45.362
But there were
few such situations.

01:01:45.660 --> 01:01:48.780
In principle, you were on
the same level energetically? -Yes.

01:01:49.660 --> 01:01:53.300
I didn't tell him what to do.
-That was the direction?

01:01:53.430 --> 01:01:55.070
It was a dialogue.

01:01:55.240 --> 01:01:58.360
We would watch a match together,
and then we would discuss what we saw.

01:01:58.474 --> 01:02:00.514
What he sees, what I see,

01:02:00.667 --> 01:02:03.309
after which we come
to a conclusion together.

01:02:03.454 --> 01:02:06.192
The conversation is not
reduced to my or his monologue,

01:02:06.344 --> 01:02:08.715
because we basically
lived together.

01:02:09.056 --> 01:02:15.340
We sleep in the same apartment
and literally spend 24 hours together.

01:02:17.723 --> 01:02:23.879
It's just easier that way, because
we exchange life and tennis experiences,

01:02:24.071 --> 01:02:26.863
because at that level, that's
the only way it can work.

01:02:32.380 --> 01:02:37.340
Ljubo, what was your worst
failure in your coaching career?

01:02:37.580 --> 01:02:39.380
Wimbledon Finals 2019.

01:02:39.620 --> 01:02:42.860
Even today, I still don't understand

01:02:43.140 --> 01:02:46.420
what happened there
and how it was even possible.

01:02:46.700 --> 01:02:48.700
Not because you
can't lose a match,

01:02:48.980 --> 01:02:52.060
not because you can't lose a match
because of match points.

01:02:54.220 --> 01:02:56.580
What did it look like?
There were two match points.

01:02:56.860 --> 01:02:59.940
Yes, but people keep talking
about those match points,

01:03:00.180 --> 01:03:04.420
but what I can say from
my position as a coach,

01:03:04.660 --> 01:03:07.740
and I know some will certainly
disagree with me,

01:03:07.940 --> 01:03:09.780
but Roger was better for five sets.

01:03:10.020 --> 01:03:14.100
If we now look at tennis, he was
the one who dictated the tempo.

01:03:14.276 --> 01:03:17.085
He lost the first set in a tie-break,
and in my opinion he played better.

01:03:17.250 --> 01:03:19.930
And I am sure that Đoković and
his team will say that it is not true.

01:03:20.220 --> 01:03:23.100
But I think Roger did everything
he needed to and could do

01:03:23.340 --> 01:03:25.620
to win that set, but he didn't.

01:03:25.860 --> 01:03:28.300
The sets he won, he won easily,
and the ones he lost,

01:03:28.500 --> 01:03:32.460
he was almost equal
to his opponent.

01:03:32.820 --> 01:03:37.705
You can lose one set like that,
but to lose three sets like that

01:03:37.939 --> 01:03:41.060
is something that rarely happens.

01:03:41.340 --> 01:03:44.780
And when it comes to match
points, even today people ask me:

01:03:45.020 --> 01:03:47.980
"Why didn't he play the service net,
why didn't he hit two first serves..."

01:03:48.220 --> 01:03:50.580
Because it shouldn't have.

01:03:50.820 --> 01:03:54.512
He came to the match ball in a
certain way, so why change it?

01:03:55.220 --> 01:03:58.700
There was another situation
that is rarely talked about,

01:03:58.940 --> 01:04:02.140
and that's after he had those
match points and lost his serve,

01:04:02.380 --> 01:04:06.060
he had break points again.
I regret that one break ball.

01:04:06.300 --> 01:04:10.100
Because he had
one passing shot,

01:04:10.340 --> 01:04:13.140
a forehand, because,
I absolutely remember

01:04:13.340 --> 01:04:16.060
every detail that we talked about,
that we were preparing

01:04:16.340 --> 01:04:21.740
and I told him that in such situations,
Novak will cover the diagonal in principle.

01:04:22.020 --> 01:04:24.500
So in such situations,
it should be played in parallel.

01:04:24.700 --> 01:04:26.820
He played diagonally,
Novak covered the diagonal,

01:04:27.020 --> 01:04:29.420
played one volley,
although it was an awkward ball,

01:04:29.511 --> 01:04:31.576
then it fell on the line,
and he lobbed it.

01:04:31.740 --> 01:04:35.140
Novak played a smash and
was served again for the match.

01:04:35.380 --> 01:04:37.460
I don't know what would
happen, maybe Novak

01:04:37.700 --> 01:04:39.860
would get a break again
and nothing would happen again.

01:04:40.100 --> 01:04:46.780
but I personally regret that point much
more than those two match points,

01:04:47.020 --> 01:04:50.020
he tried to score and missed,
then came to the net,

01:04:50.300 --> 01:04:53.500
and Novak scored.
-That was a decisive moment.

01:04:53.980 --> 01:04:56.900
One more thing I regret.
I talked about that.

01:04:57.180 --> 01:05:04.100
Match before that one.
Match against Nadal 2019

01:05:05.100 --> 01:05:10.060
was the biggest match
in my coaching career.

01:05:10.860 --> 01:05:13.301
Because it's a match, at least
I have that feeling,

01:05:13.446 --> 01:05:15.006
I don't know if it's true,

01:05:15.207 --> 01:05:17.840
you can ask Roger about that
when you have the chance,

01:05:18.104 --> 01:05:23.144
I think I maybe contributed the most
to the result of that semi-finals match

01:05:23.268 --> 01:05:25.434
Wimbledon against Nadal.

01:05:25.551 --> 01:05:28.224
But everyone talks about the final,
which was the way it was,

01:05:28.483 --> 01:05:30.483
and nobody remembers
that semi-finals.

01:05:32.180 --> 01:05:38.740
Ljubo, in addition to the academy,
you accepted another job. -I'm bored.

01:05:41.860 --> 01:05:47.580
You are currently in an executive
position in the French Tennis Federation.

01:05:47.900 --> 01:05:52.460
You were given a free hands
to organize the entire system.

01:05:52.700 --> 01:05:57.340
We all know what France means,
in sports in general, as well as in tennis.

01:05:57.620 --> 01:06:02.380
It is an organized system,
healthy, expensive.

01:06:02.620 --> 01:06:04.940
How did this
collaboration come about,

01:06:05.180 --> 01:06:08.537
this offer, and how do you
see yourself in it?

01:06:09.700 --> 01:06:13.220
Let me just say that my
official title is Director...

01:06:15.380 --> 01:06:21.620
Developments? -High performance,
actually of everything

01:06:22.060 --> 01:06:25.175
that is the competitive part.

01:06:28.100 --> 01:06:31.441
How did it come about?
It happened in London at the Laver Cup,

01:06:31.595 --> 01:06:33.715
where Roger ended his career.

01:06:33.923 --> 01:06:36.523
There he was the president
of the French federation,

01:06:36.772 --> 01:06:40.113
whom I knew from before.
He was the director

01:06:40.360 --> 01:06:43.136
of the tournament in Lyon,
which I won in 2001.

01:06:43.326 --> 01:06:45.206
Everything worked out.

01:06:45.361 --> 01:06:48.464
So Gilles Moretton asked
me what I was planning now.

01:06:48.653 --> 01:06:50.213
I said I don't know.

01:06:50.328 --> 01:06:54.750
I didn't want to train a player again,
although I had interesting offers.

01:06:55.293 --> 01:06:59.282
I didn't feel like going
back to coaching.

01:06:59.686 --> 01:07:03.508
Then he asked me if I was interested
in helping French tennis.

01:07:03.730 --> 01:07:06.540
That seemed very exotic to me,
because we know that

01:07:06.780 --> 01:07:11.380
the French are very closed,
they don't let anyone in.

01:07:11.900 --> 01:07:14.580
The French tennis federation is
the largest federation in the world.

01:07:14.820 --> 01:07:18.060
There are 1 100 000 licensed players.

01:07:18.260 --> 01:07:22.740
1 100 000? -Yes, with licenses.
Not recreationists, but competitors.

01:07:23.500 --> 01:07:26.980
So it's one huge
piece of machinery.

01:07:28.260 --> 01:07:33.580
He invited me to Paris in November,
in Bersa to get to know everything,

01:07:33.820 --> 01:07:37.700
because it's a huge structure,
and I really didn't know how it works.

01:07:37.980 --> 01:07:44.771
So from the beginning of 2023
I tried to understand how things work.

01:07:46.622 --> 01:07:52.191
I followed some players
individually until September,

01:07:52.546 --> 01:07:55.586
and since then I officially
became the director of that,

01:07:56.100 --> 01:07:59.940
so to speak, competitive part.
Next year is the Olympic year,

01:08:00.380 --> 01:08:05.020
﻿I am responsible for all national
teams and Olympic teams.

01:08:05.980 --> 01:08:08.740
Of course, the Olympics
in  Paris is a huge pressure.

01:08:08.980 --> 01:08:12.380
You don't even have time to list
everything? -Yes, there is a lot.

01:08:13.220 --> 01:08:15.860
Honestly, it's hard to finish
everything well.

01:08:16.540 --> 01:08:21.820
I would like to be in several
places at the same time.

01:08:22.140 --> 01:08:26.700
However, I still can't do it,
but I'm working on it.

01:08:26.940 --> 01:08:29.860
It would be good if it was possible.

01:08:30.380 --> 01:08:36.180
I'm interested, because
a lot of people say it can be done.

01:08:37.220 --> 01:08:41.726
Some people think
that I shouldn't be there.

01:08:42.940 --> 01:08:46.540
I don't react to negative energy,
but to when they say it's impossible,

01:08:46.940 --> 01:08:49.620
then I react to it.

01:08:50.300 --> 01:08:55.340
When they say that there is no chance,
I'll show they that it can.

01:08:56.420 --> 01:09:01.740
Are there any potential Federer,
Đoković among those French?

01:09:01.980 --> 01:09:06.420
It's a wide base, is there anyone...
-There are many talents.

01:09:06.740 --> 01:09:09.660
My official position is 15+,

01:09:09.900 --> 01:09:13.580
but I follow what's happening
below that as well.

01:09:13.860 --> 01:09:24.100
You have many kids playing tennis,
a tennis culture, that machinery...

01:09:24.460 --> 01:09:30.100
Of course, every generation
has a potential great player.

01:09:30.580 --> 01:09:33.229
However, something is happening
to them from the age of 15.

01:09:33.372 --> 01:09:36.807
I am now responsible for them,
we need to find out what is happening.

01:09:42.100 --> 01:09:45.780
Ljubo, it is inevitable, we must
talk about Novak Đoković,

01:09:46.220 --> 01:09:53.152
since this show will be watched
in our region, in ex-yu states.

01:09:53.900 --> 01:09:56.980
He is the undisputed king here.

01:09:57.500 --> 01:10:00.300
You, maybe you have
the complete picture.

01:10:00.540 --> 01:10:05.517
You played with him, beat him
and coached his biggest rival.

01:10:05.821 --> 01:10:09.620
I know you will be subjective
because of Federer,

01:10:09.900 --> 01:10:15.598
but explain to me this phenomenon,
his functioning of reason.

01:10:15.965 --> 01:10:19.285
Not all those grand slams, titles,
but what drives him forward?

01:10:19.580 --> 01:10:27.020
What is he made of? -Actually,
everyone asks me about Roger.

01:10:27.980 --> 01:10:31.780
When I am asked about Đoković,
usually they ask about his record.

01:10:31.980 --> 01:10:36.260
Is it the biggest record?
So the fun is over.

01:10:36.740 --> 01:10:41.420
However, what few people know
is that Novak and me are friends.

01:10:41.740 --> 01:10:45.700
We trained together. When
Novak was 17-18 years old,

01:10:45.940 --> 01:10:50.100
he came to Ricardo P., that was
in 2005, when I was at my peak.

01:10:50.340 --> 01:10:54.220
We trained together for a while.
I was his mentor.

01:10:54.580 --> 01:10:59.380
He still mentions today how
I advised him which wires to use.

01:11:01.220 --> 01:11:06.340
So, it often happens that the media
try to provoke us into arguing.

01:11:07.260 --> 01:11:09.710
They want to put some
words in my mouth.

01:11:09.895 --> 01:11:12.509
However, Novak and I
know each other very well.

01:11:12.651 --> 01:11:15.599
We went through some
things together.

01:11:16.364 --> 01:11:19.112
Our family members
are also close-knit.

01:11:20.180 --> 01:11:26.169
I will return to the question...
Novak is an indestructible tank.

01:11:27.140 --> 01:11:31.820
When he sets a goal, he tries to
achieve it. There is no stopping.

01:11:32.420 --> 01:11:34.940
As long as he has a goal,
he goes towards it.

01:11:35.260 --> 01:11:40.060
At a few moments in his career,
when his goal was not clear,

01:11:40.300 --> 01:11:51.331
or there was none, he lost himself,
but as soon as his aim was returned,

01:11:51.976 --> 01:11:54.416
then he is infallible.

01:11:57.101 --> 01:12:02.595
Is there still fire in him,
because he is a sportsman

01:12:04.680 --> 01:12:09.976
who operates that way,
feeding off negative energy.

01:12:10.500 --> 01:12:15.580
We can often see him arguing,
how he is provoking the audience,

01:12:15.900 --> 01:12:18.980
because he needs that
to move and lift him up.

01:12:21.140 --> 01:12:28.540
It's absolutely fascinating to me,
when you watch his videos today,

01:12:28.820 --> 01:12:33.540
and 10-15 years ago, the way
he moves, there is no difference.

01:12:33.820 --> 01:12:37.300
Of course, it is better now,
it wasn’t better 10-15 years ago.

01:12:37.422 --> 01:12:40.142
When you watch the video of Nadal
and Ferrer, 10 years ago,

01:12:40.310 --> 01:12:41.950
you will see the difference.

01:12:42.207 --> 01:12:45.127
So, he has succeeded
in everything he does.

01:12:45.297 --> 01:12:48.777
His body is perfect,
even at 30 and more. I don’t know...

01:12:49.008 --> 01:12:53.435
But that is irrelevant because
he is not physically that age.

01:12:53.688 --> 01:12:59.168
He will play and win as long
the goal is in the frist place.

01:12:59.408 --> 01:13:02.088
At the moment when there is no
target, or if he is in the wrong place,

01:13:02.258 --> 01:13:05.858
then its results will be bad,
but the body is absolutely perfect.

01:13:06.460 --> 01:13:08.980
I totally get it,
thanks for the answer.

01:13:09.580 --> 01:13:15.748
Do you think there is similar
potential in our region?

01:13:16.940 --> 01:13:20.380
This doesn’t exist in the world,
such unique potential.

01:13:20.620 --> 01:13:25.780
That's my opinion. A tennis
player will never be born again

01:13:26.060 --> 01:13:28.820
who will win 20 Grand Slams.

01:13:29.780 --> 01:13:34.260
That's how we talked about Stefan
Egberg? About Pete Sampras?

01:13:34.500 --> 01:13:36.900
Yes, that was also wrong.
Maybe I'm wrong too.

01:13:37.140 --> 01:13:42.740
Time will tell, but in the region...
There is always talent.

01:13:44.300 --> 01:13:49.060
I don't want us to take Đoković
as an example, that's impossible.

01:13:49.700 --> 01:13:53.380
Maybe I expressed myself
badly, but is there anyone...?

01:13:53.526 --> 01:13:55.514
There are always talents.

01:13:55.716 --> 01:13:59.396
The difference between our region
and France is that in France,

01:13:59.567 --> 01:14:01.727
each generation has many talents.

01:14:02.178 --> 01:14:05.098
In our region,
fewer children play tennis

01:14:05.518 --> 01:14:08.838
and every 3-4 generations
have one talent.

01:14:09.220 --> 01:14:12.200
In Croatia it is Dino Prižmić,
in Serbia it is Medjedović...

01:14:13.260 --> 01:14:17.740
There are, they appear,
but not very intensively,

01:14:17.980 --> 01:14:21.340
as in some countries,
such as France.

01:14:22.367 --> 01:14:31.552
Does your approach with infrastructure
and youth bring a better future?

01:14:33.055 --> 01:14:36.735
Or do you think there will be
some kind of stagnation?

01:14:37.300 --> 01:14:42.347
Infrastructure doesn’t make champions,
at least we from the region know that.

01:14:42.941 --> 01:14:47.678
Conditions don’t make champions,
but mentality and way of thinking.

01:14:48.019 --> 01:14:55.059
If you manage to instill this in
athletes and with good conditions,

01:14:55.540 --> 01:14:59.060
then there will be an explosion
of excellent results. I don't know...

01:14:59.340 --> 01:15:03.580
The fact is that I am not preparing
the Academy for the region.

01:15:03.820 --> 01:15:09.700
I work for world tennis and I actually
have few tennis players from the region.

01:15:10.180 --> 01:15:12.820
Tennis is an individual sport.

01:15:13.100 --> 01:15:16.620
This is what I am trying
to explain to the French.

01:15:16.860 --> 01:15:21.300
We, as an association,
can’t guaranteee.

01:15:21.624 --> 01:15:24.472
Our role isn’t to create champions,

01:15:24.711 --> 01:15:29.792
but we guide and connect them
with quality people.

01:15:30.060 --> 01:15:33.580
They must take responsibility
for that project.

01:15:33.900 --> 01:15:37.125
In individual sports, the athlete
must take responsibility.

01:15:37.358 --> 01:15:40.369
And he is the only one in charge
and responsible for success.

01:15:40.638 --> 01:15:43.147
It is clear that there are people
who will help him.

01:15:43.389 --> 01:15:48.039
But, if we think that this gym,
the Academy or some association

01:15:48.162 --> 01:15:51.046
will make him a tennis player,
that is not possible.

01:15:51.223 --> 01:15:53.625
That must be clear to everyone.

01:15:53.838 --> 01:15:57.773
We are here to help,
not to work for someone else.

01:15:59.740 --> 01:16:08.660
Siener, Rune, Alcraz,
can that "hype" be made again?

01:16:09.020 --> 01:16:13.180
Like Đoković, Nadal, Federer
that they can reach those 15, 20?

01:16:13.420 --> 01:16:18.863
Are they the new leadership
in the world of tennis? -Yes.

01:16:20.060 --> 01:16:23.860
I think that the three of them
are a new generation of tennis.

01:16:24.060 --> 01:16:26.500
Who will win Grand Slams?
I don't know how many they will win.

01:16:26.740 --> 01:16:29.900
I mention again
what they have won so far.

01:16:30.580 --> 01:16:36.820
But Siener, Alcaraz, or
Alcaraz, Siener, then Rune...

01:16:37.180 --> 01:16:41.532
We can't put them in
the same sentence.

01:16:43.000 --> 01:16:47.220
What those two are doing
is incomparable with Rune.

01:16:47.540 --> 01:16:51.220
At the moment,
they are young and phenomenal.

01:16:51.860 --> 01:16:56.380
We have this contrast of tennis,
character, personality,

01:16:56.820 --> 01:17:01.460
which has nothing to do with each
other. They are highly respected.

01:17:01.700 --> 01:17:04.860
And we have the same respect
that Nadal and Feder had.

01:17:05.060 --> 01:17:09.540
Alcaz and Siener trained together
this winter. -Is that strange?

01:17:09.780 --> 01:17:13.980
It is a wonderful positive message
about what sport is.

01:17:14.860 --> 01:17:20.340
I'm also interested
to see what happens.

01:17:20.940 --> 01:17:28.895
These three leave, in fact,
one has already done it.

01:17:29.900 --> 01:17:36.460
They are phenomenal ambassadors
of our sport, Alcaraz, Siener and Rune.

01:17:42.060 --> 01:17:48.700
You said that you participated in
the increase of prize funds in tennis?

01:17:49.020 --> 01:17:54.340
Is there a rule, because there is
progress in all sports,

01:17:54.700 --> 01:17:58.253
which would you like to change?

01:18:04.049 --> 01:18:07.558
You mean the sports rules? -Yes.

01:18:12.756 --> 01:18:16.615
As far as tennis is concerned,
we are way ahead.

01:18:17.035 --> 01:18:21.571
We have introduced
electronic calling lines...

01:18:22.700 --> 01:18:27.940
In the 80s, there was that Cyclops,
if you remember, at Wimbledon...

01:18:29.740 --> 01:18:32.820
When you touch it... -Yes.
That was in the 80s.

01:18:33.140 --> 01:18:35.340
Well, then Hawkeye...

01:18:35.780 --> 01:18:39.940
So we are way ahead.
-Everything is transparent with you.

01:18:42.540 --> 01:18:47.900
I will be free to say that tennis
is the fairest sport.

01:18:48.300 --> 01:18:50.620
You don't have to have a coach
who will put you in the game

01:18:50.860 --> 01:18:53.060
or he doesn't want to.
It's all up to you.

01:18:53.300 --> 01:18:57.260
The player has absolute responsibility
for everything that happens to him.

01:18:57.460 --> 01:18:59.780
He chooses the coach,
the tournaments he will play.

01:19:00.020 --> 01:19:03.260
A mark is left on the ground
if the ball falls.

01:19:04.378 --> 01:19:09.760
Of course, children who grow up
in France don’t have

01:19:09.932 --> 01:19:13.221
the same conditions as children
who grow up somewhere

01:19:13.408 --> 01:19:15.688
where there aren’t tennis
courts or balls.

01:19:15.928 --> 01:19:20.300
But, if you manage to overcome
the initial conditions,

01:19:20.566 --> 01:19:23.378
it’s the fairest possible sport,

01:19:23.645 --> 01:19:29.445
and the second most popular sport
in the world, after football.

01:19:29.980 --> 01:19:35.420
It can still be put to much better use,
but as far as sports rules go,

01:19:35.620 --> 01:19:38.540
I'm a traditionalist.

01:19:39.332 --> 01:19:43.682
I love tradition and I wouldn't
change anything, absolutely.

01:19:43.940 --> 01:19:48.300
Maybe let, but that's little.
-I'm hearing that for the first time.

01:19:48.540 --> 01:19:50.860
So, everything is okay for you?

01:19:51.100 --> 01:19:53.140
Ljubo, now a family question.

01:19:53.300 --> 01:19:57.620
Zara and Leonardo, your children,
do they play sports? -Yes.

01:19:58.220 --> 01:20:03.980
Unfortunately, Leonardo plays
tennis. -I hope you aren’t his coach?

01:20:04.660 --> 01:20:11.020
Absolutely no, I avoid it.
They go to school, in Monaco.

01:20:11.540 --> 01:20:15.940
Everything is in the best possible
order. They speak five languages.

01:20:16.380 --> 01:20:21.900
I am very proud and happy. Leonardo
loves tennis and enjoys playing it.

01:20:22.140 --> 01:20:27.340
He is taller than me, and he is 15.
He had a back problem last year.

01:20:27.540 --> 01:20:33.380
He is growing, but he will play tennis,
at what level, time will tell.

01:20:33.620 --> 01:20:39.180
He comes here often, to the Academy.
Zara also plays tennis, but less so.

01:20:39.420 --> 01:20:42.380
She is not very active,
once or twice a week.

01:20:42.620 --> 01:20:46.140
They play sports,
everything is as it should be.

01:20:47.140 --> 01:20:53.060
We often talk about my childhood
and theirs, about these differences.

01:20:53.190 --> 01:20:57.870
I am proud to be able to give them
the childhood they have.

01:20:57.995 --> 01:21:00.635
Afterwards, they wil build
their own lives.

01:21:03.060 --> 01:21:08.380
We know you work for Sky Italia?
You are sometimes in my position.

01:21:08.700 --> 01:21:15.860
We are colleagues in business,
so tell me how you feel on this side,

01:21:16.140 --> 01:21:23.740
when is tennis commented?
-I like that part of the job very much.

01:21:25.180 --> 01:21:27.900
I remember that I was very nervous
when I interviewed Rodger

01:21:28.220 --> 01:21:32.460
for the first time,
more than 10 years ago.

01:21:32.780 --> 01:21:38.660
Then, you understand me? -Yes.
Interview preparation, questions...

01:21:38.860 --> 01:21:42.020
I called his manager to ask him
what I could ask him.

01:21:42.260 --> 01:21:47.060
He told me that Roger told him,
"I could ask him what I wanted".

01:21:47.620 --> 01:21:51.820
Then it creates additional pressure.
Now I sometimes do interviews.

01:21:52.100 --> 01:21:57.100
I interviewed Tsitsipas
and Naratilova, last year.

01:21:57.340 --> 01:22:00.940
That was fun. I interviewed
Marina Navratilova.

01:22:01.180 --> 01:22:03.340
And she says I do it very well.

01:22:03.580 --> 01:22:06.940
So, I do have the talent,
but I don't have the time.

01:22:07.220 --> 01:22:11.900
But, when I work for the Italian Sky,
I basically work from the studio.

01:22:12.180 --> 01:22:15.220
Preparation of the match,
analysis after the match..

01:22:15.420 --> 01:22:17.900
Sometimes I comment on the match.

01:22:18.180 --> 01:22:25.174
I love it, and I like the way
the Italians do it, with humor.

01:22:26.183 --> 01:22:28.703
I like that very much.

01:22:30.140 --> 01:22:33.340
Ljubo, finally, the last question...

01:22:33.470 --> 01:22:36.285
There have been so many
failures throughout my,

01:22:36.422 --> 01:22:38.422
your and everyone's career...

01:22:38.780 --> 01:22:41.980
Now you are a coach
and you work with young people.

01:22:42.260 --> 01:22:44.980
What kind of approach
do you have

01:22:45.260 --> 01:22:48.220
when you are explaining
to them how to behave?

01:22:48.500 --> 01:22:54.540
With defeat and rising, after a fall,
how to make two, three, five steps,

01:22:54.940 --> 01:23:00.060
every day, and what is the final
message in this show?

01:23:00.260 --> 01:23:04.780
How to move forward?
-Work, just work.

01:23:05.060 --> 01:23:12.620
No matter how much knowledge
we have, nothing can replace work.

01:23:13.620 --> 01:23:16.940
It is the absolute
base for everything.

01:23:17.180 --> 01:23:24.300
And you have to be persistent, because
the one who is the most precise

01:23:24.580 --> 01:23:28.615
and the best doesn’t succeed, but
the one who is the most persistent,

01:23:28.780 --> 01:23:31.185
manages to fall and rise again.

01:23:31.923 --> 01:23:38.283
In sports, as in life, there is
no limited number of attempts.

01:23:39.220 --> 01:23:42.332
At the end of your career,
nobody mentions you,

01:23:42.416 --> 01:23:44.696
except for this show of yours.

01:23:44.857 --> 01:23:48.364
But, they ask what you won and
what are your career successes.

01:23:51.140 --> 01:23:55.860
All this that we talked about
is necessary for success.

01:23:56.820 --> 01:24:00.820
There isn’t a single person
or athlete who tried everything

01:24:01.100 --> 01:24:04.300
and knew everything
from the beginning.

01:24:04.540 --> 01:24:08.900
No one had everything go smoothly
from the very beginning, from day one.

01:24:09.420 --> 01:24:15.380
If something doesn't work today,
try again 200-300 times.

01:24:15.820 --> 01:24:19.540
Don't give up, because you
never know where that key is.

01:24:19.780 --> 01:24:23.140
I really think, the most persistent
ones succeed in the end,

01:24:23.460 --> 01:24:28.100
and those who manage
to rise after falling.

01:24:29.340 --> 01:24:32.940
Ljubo, I am speechless.
Thank you!

